(3699, 287267, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1433910790;s:7:"mytitle";s:40:"Irritated with Burma, China Woos Suu Kyi";s:6:"mylink";s:75:"http://www.irrawaddy.org/burma/irritated-with-burma-china-woos-suu-kyi.html";s:6:"mydesc";s:4876:"<div><a href="http://www.irrawaddy.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Suu-Kyi-China.jpg"><img src="http://www.irrawaddy.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Suu-Kyi-China.jpg" alt="Myanmar''s pro-democracy leader Aung San Suu Kyi (C) leaves her National League for Democracy''s headquarters after meeting with ethnic leaders of her party in Yangon November 16, 2010. China is confident that Myanmar will continue its process of peace and ethnic reconciliation, the Foreign Ministry said on Tuesday, in Beijing''s first official reaction to the release of Suu Kyi. REUTERS/Soe Zeya Tun (MYANMAR - Tags: POLITICS) - RTXUP3Z" width="610" height="399"></a><p>Myanmar&rsquo;s pro-democracy leader Aung San Suu Kyi (C) leaves her National League for Democracy&rsquo;s headquarters after meeting with ethnic leaders of her party in Yangon November 16, 2010. China is confident that Myanmar will continue its process of peace and ethnic reconciliation, the Foreign Ministry said on Tuesday, in Beijing&rsquo;s first official reaction to the release of Suu Kyi. REUTERS/Soe Zeya Tun (MYANMAR &ndash; Tags: POLITICS) &ndash; RTXUP3Z</p></div>\n<p>BEIJING &mdash; Chinese leaders will woo Burma&rsquo;s opposition leader and Nobel laureate Aung San Suu Kyi on her first visit to the country, a snub for the quasi-military government whose fighting with rebels along China&rsquo;s border has angered Beijing.</p>\n<p>But the visit will also be awkward for China&rsquo;s ruling Communist Party which has invited Suu Kyi, as her fellow Nobel Peace Prize laureate Liu Xiaobo remains in jail and Chinese President Xi Jinping is overseeing a sweeping crackdown on dissent.</p>\n<p>Activists are putting pressure on Suu Kyi to make some reference to Liu&rsquo;s detention during the visit, and if she does, it will be a huge embarrassment for Beijing.</p>\n<p>Suu Kyi will meet Xi and Premier Li Keqiang on the June 10-14 trip, according to her National League for Democracy (NLD), although China has kept details under wraps and it is not known if she will make any public appearances.</p>\n<p>Since taking power in March 2011, Burma&rsquo;s reformist government has sought to decrease the heavy dependence on China that grew when Burma was a pariah state under military rule. Beijing has watched nervously as the United States lifted some sanctions and engaged with the semi-civilian government.</p>\n<p>But China has been keen to reach out to Suu Kyi. The NLD is expected to do well in a general election in November, the first free vote in the country for 25 years. Suu Kyi is excluded from the presidency under a military-drafted constitution, but her power and influence will grow if the NLD performs as well as expected.</p>\n<p>The China-Burma relationship has been strained this year as stray army shells from fighting between the Burmese government and ethnic Chinese rebels killed at least five people in China&rsquo;s Yunnan province in March.</p>\n<p>Lin Xixing, a Burma expert at Guangzhou&rsquo;s Jinan University, said China was fed up with the government ignoring their protests on the border violence.</p>\n<p>&ldquo;Perhaps Aung San Suu Kyi can bring her influence to bear on ending the conflict,&rdquo; Lin said, adding it was highly unusual for Xi to meet any kind of foreign opposition figure.</p>\n<p>&ldquo;In any case, it will be good to have her here to get to know her and explain our policy towards Myanmar.&rdquo;</p>\n<p>Chinese state media has praised Suu Kyi ahead of her arrival, saying that with Burma&rsquo;s democratisation the old certainties about the reliability of Sino-Burma ties were no longer there.</p>\n<p>&ldquo;We believe that Aung San Suu Kyi will become a good friend of China&rsquo;s,&rdquo; the Global Times, an influential tabloid published by the Communist Party&rsquo;s official People&rsquo;s Daily, wrote in an editorial.</p>\n<p>The official Xinhua news agency added in its own commentary that it was important Suu Kyi develop &ldquo;a very thorough understanding of the special bond between the two countries&rdquo;.</p>\n<p>Phyo Zayar Thaw, one of the two MPs travelling with Suu Kyi, said that he did not know if issues of human rights would be raised.</p>\n<p>Hu Jia, a Chinese prominent dissident and close friend of Liu Xiaobo, told Reuters that if Suu Kyi does not call for Liu&rsquo;s release, &ldquo;it will bring some degree of regret&rdquo;.</p>\n<p>&ldquo;Ms. Aung San Suu Kyi is a Nobel Peace Prize Laureate and in Chinese prison, there sits another Nobel Peace Prize Laureate,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;This is an unavoidable topic for the Chinese Communist Party and is extremely embarrassing.&rdquo;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.irrawaddy.org/burma/irritated-with-burma-china-woos-suu-kyi.html">Irritated with Burma, China Woos Suu Kyi</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.irrawaddy.org/">The Irrawaddy</a>.</p>";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:3:"T G";s:12:"itemcategory";s:30:"Burma, BEN BLANCHARD / REUTERS";s:7:"mycatid";s:1:"2";s:7:"myGroup";s:13:"The Irrawaddy";s:6:"feedID";i:53149;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
