(13832, 289699, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1434078056;s:7:"mytitle";s:28:"Cable shows cartel’s reach";s:6:"mylink";s:70:"http://www.opendevelopmentcambodia.net/news/cable-shows-cartels-reach/";s:6:"mydesc";s:1136:"<p>A sex-trafficking network that included &ldquo;high-ranking&rdquo; government officials and had infiltrated Cambodian law enforcement agencies and NGOs for years worked to cover up Vietnamese sex rings and collect payoffs from illegal prostitution establishments in Phnom Penh.</p>\n<p>However, four years after a court finally convicted the police official at the network&rsquo;s head, the same man still works as a high-ranking official in the Phnom Penh Municipal Police.</p>\n<p>The group was first revealed when several of its members were convicted in 2011. But a&nbsp;<a href="http://www.phnompenhpost.com/sites/default/files/ce5070232b3f9c4d6f3f01e60b2ff7572464b3bf2246eec5758a1d8d317d3a65.pdf" target="_blank">confidential</a><a href="http://www.phnompenhpost.com/sites/default/files/ce5070232b3f9c4d6f3f01e60b2ff7572464b3bf2246eec5758a1d8d317d3a65.pdf" target="_blank"> US State Department cable</a> obtained by the <em>Post</em> under a Freedom of Information Act request and interviews with top anti-trafficking officials and a senior member of the organisation have shed new light on the reach of this cartel. &hellip;</p>";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:11:"Ratana Pich";s:12:"itemcategory";s:165:"Eam Rattana, Phnom Penh Municipal Anti-Human Trafficking Police Commissioner, Phnom Penh Municipal Police Commissioner, US embassy in Phnom Penh, US State Department";s:7:"mycatid";s:1:"6";s:7:"myGroup";s:25:"Open Development Cambodia";s:6:"feedID";i:53127;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
