(19467, 291104, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1427895139;s:7:"mytitle";s:24:"Following the ASEAN beat";s:6:"mylink";s:50:"http://www.aseannews.net/following-the-asean-beat/";s:6:"mydesc";s:2477:"<p><em>Editorial, The ASEAN Beat &ndash; magazine produced at the Reporting ASEAN: A Media Forum, from 31 Mar to 2 Apr 2015</em></p>\n<p>****</p>\n<p>ASEAN has become a bit of a mantra in media and elsewhere in the region. Signs, slogans about ASEAN adorn airports down to cigarette lighters these days. But while ASEAN is something often heard or mentioned, it is not always fully understood, and certainly not in enough detail.<span></span></p>\n<p>&lsquo;The ASEAN Beat&rsquo; is a contribution to telling the ASEAN story, following issues being discussed at the &lsquo;Reporting ASEAN&rsquo; media forum in Bangkok but also those beyond it.<a href="http://www.aseannews.net/following-the-asean-beat/01-4/" rel="attachment wp-att-1673"><img title="01" src="http://www.aseannews.net/wp-content/uploads/013-201x300.png" alt="" width="238" height="355"></a></p>\n<p>To this end, the word &lsquo;beat&rsquo; in this magazine&rsquo;s name holds two meanings. First, it refers to deepening integration and linkages among ASEAN countries (and hopefully peoples too) and the &lsquo;busyness&rsquo; and vibrancy that comes with this, Second, it refers to the definition of ASEAN as a news beat, one may yet happen in newsrooms in the years to come.</p>\n<p>It is time to follow the ASEAN beat because regional integration &ndash; its opportunities, implications and social and development challenges &ndash; is in many ways the biggest story unfolding in this region. It is right in our midst, but we &ndash; whether as journalists, information gatekeepers or audiences &ndash;&nbsp;do not know enough about it. In fact, many journalists find it a boring, nothing-happening-all-talk venue, and many people find ASEAN far removed from their daily existence.</p>\n<p>And yet because it has potential to shape the lives of ASEAN&rsquo;s constituency, journalists need to be able to tell the story of ASEAN integration better&nbsp; &ndash; and shape critical stories from the public&rsquo;s need to know (and ask) instead of following the lead of states, officials and diplomats. Perhaps it is also time to revisit old news habits of defining news as something that needs to have a VIP minister or diplomat in it, of classifying ASEAN as a foreign-policy story only when integration crosses into many other beats, of limiting &lsquo;ASEAN news&rsquo; to ASEAN events or summits.</p>\n<p>See you on the ASEAN beat.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Johanna Son</p>\n<p>Editor, The ASEAN Beat</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:9:"Admin IPS";s:12:"itemcategory";s:99:"Features, Reporting ASEAN: 2015 and Beyond Series, The ASEAN Beat, aec, asean, regional integration";s:7:"mycatid";N;s:7:"myGroup";N;s:6:"feedID";i:53203;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
