(19575, 291131, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1415640789;s:7:"mytitle";s:40:"Economic integration: The flying factory";s:6:"mylink";s:139:"http://www.economist.com/news/special-report/21631799-asia-has-built-web-economic-interdependence-which-china-would-be-ill-advised?fsrc=rss";s:6:"mydesc";s:1429:"UK Only Article:&amp;nbsp;\n                    standard article        \n        \n\n\n\n      Issue:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    The Pacific Age        \n        \n\n\n\n      Fly Title:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Economic integration        \n        \n\n\n\n      Rubric:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Asia has built a web of economic interdependence which China would be ill-advised to unravel        \n        \n\n\n\n\n\n      Main image:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    20141115_SRP003_0.jpg        \n        \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nIN 1999 ANDY CHAN, a middle-aged Hong Kong businessman, set up a company in Shenzhen, just over the border on the Chinese mainland, making pretty sets of bath soap to fill American Christmas stockings. They were sold at $10 apiece at retailers like Walmart. His firm made and shipped them, by the hundreds of thousands in each steel container, for just $4. In the first few years his firm made a bomb. He paid his workers a pittance, 290 yuan (then $35) a month, and imported his raw materials from Malaysia for next to nothing. But then China&rsquo;s exchange rate soared, his workers&rsquo; wages rose almost tenfold, the authorities started enforcing overtime rules and competition turned brutal. The business collapsed. Now he is a taxi driver. &ldquo;You can&rsquo;t do this business in Shenzhen any ...&lt;div class="og_rss_groups"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:0:"";s:12:"itemcategory";N;s:7:"mycatid";N;s:7:"myGroup";N;s:6:"feedID";i:53182;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
