(19583, 291133, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1408028363;s:7:"mytitle";s:20:"Banyan: Future tense";s:6:"mylink";s:144:"http://www.economist.com/news/asia/21612218-america-china-and-south-east-asia-continue-talk-past-each-other-over-south-china-sea-future?fsrc=rss";s:6:"mydesc";s:1470:"UK Only Article:&amp;nbsp;\n                    standard article        \n        \n\n\n\n      Issue:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Back to Iraq        \n        \n\n\n\n      Fly Title:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Banyan        \n        \n\n\n\n      Rubric:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    America, China and South-East Asia continue to talk past each other over the South China Sea        \n        \n\n\n\n\n\n      Main image:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    20140816_ASD000_0.jpg        \n        \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTENSION in the South China Sea has now reached the point where references to tension have become an issue. &ldquo;Someone has been exaggerating or even playing up the so-called tension in the South China Sea,&rdquo; Wang Yi, China&rsquo;s foreign minister, said on August 9th. By &ldquo;someone&rdquo;, of course, he meant America. He was speaking in Naypyidaw, Myanmar&rsquo;s capital, where the ten foreign ministers of ASEAN, the Association of South-East Asian Nations, were holding their annual meeting. So when they agreed on a communiqu&eacute; referring to &ldquo;increased tensions&rdquo; in the sea, many scored it as a diplomatic victory for the United States.\nAmerican officials saw the inclusion of the phrase as a sign that ASEAN&rsquo;s members were readier to present a united front against Chinese aggression towards rival claimants to territory ...&lt;div class="og_rss_groups"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:0:"";s:12:"itemcategory";N;s:7:"mycatid";N;s:7:"myGroup";N;s:6:"feedID";i:53182;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
