(19643, 291148, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1430406798;s:7:"mytitle";s:33:"The South China Sea: Making waves";s:6:"mylink";s:116:"http://www.economist.com/news/china/21650150-china-tries-strengthen-its-hand-dangerous-dispute-making-waves?fsrc=rss";s:6:"mydesc";s:1434:"UK Only Article:&amp;nbsp;\n                    standard article        \n        \n\n\n\n      Issue:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Who should govern Britain?        \n        \n\n\n\n      Fly Title:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    The South China Sea        \n        \n\n\n\n      Rubric:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    China tries to strengthen its hand in a dangerous dispute        \n        \n\n\n\n\n      Location:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    BEIJING        \n        \n\n\n\n      Main image:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    20150502_CNP004_1.jpg        \n        \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nIN NOVEMBER, after months of frantic land reclamation in the South China Sea aimed at boosting its vast territorial claim there, China tried a subtler approach. It opened a think-tank in Arlington, Virginia&mdash;an outpost of its National Institute for South China Sea Studies on Hainan, a tropical (and indisputably Chinese) island on the sea&rsquo;s northern shore. One role for the new think-tank is to make an academic case for China&rsquo;s vaguely backed assertion that most of the strategically vital waters are within its domain&mdash;despite rival claims by South-East Asian countries. &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;\nOn April 16th the Institute for China-America Studies, as the Virginia-based centre is called, held a conference at a hotel in ...&lt;div class="og_rss_groups"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:0:"";s:12:"itemcategory";N;s:7:"mycatid";N;s:7:"myGroup";N;s:6:"feedID";i:53171;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
