(19663, 291153, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1427056882;s:7:"mytitle";s:61:"The Economist explains: How Singapore gained its independence";s:6:"mylink";s:88:"http://www.economist.com/blogs/economist-explains/2015/03/economist-explains-22?fsrc=rss";s:6:"mydesc";s:1503:"TRIBUTES are pouring in for Lee Kuan Yew, Singapore&rsquo;s first prime minister, who died in the early hours of March 23rd (Singapore time). But Mr Lee&rsquo;s grand stature belies the oddity of the island city-state, separated from the southern tip of Malaysia by a narrow strait, which&amp;nbsp;he helped to build. Only 30 miles (48km) across at its widest point, it takes up little more than half the space occupied by New York&rsquo;s five boroughs; with 5.5m inhabitants it is much less populous. On a per person basis Singapore is far richer than its neighbours in the region, and it is the only country in South-East Asia in which ethnic-Chinese citizens make up the majority. How did it come to be?Singapore&rsquo;s modern history began in the early nineteenth century, when Stamford Raffles, a British administrator based in Java, chose to develop the island as a trading post for the East India Company. It was one of three cities which later formed a wealthy British colony known as the Straits Settlements (the others were Melaka&mdash;which is not far from Kuala Lumpur&mdash;and Penang, an island just off Malaysia&rsquo;s north-west coast). Singapore&rsquo;s colonial governors encouraged workers to migrate from Britain&rsquo;s colonies in South Asia; they also welcomed ethnic-Chinese traders and labourers who moved from mainland China and from across South-East Asia, and who eventually formed the island&rsquo;s largest single ethnic ...&lt;div class="og_rss_groups"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:0:"";s:12:"itemcategory";N;s:7:"mycatid";N;s:7:"myGroup";N;s:6:"feedID";i:53171;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
