(19683, 291158, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1415633455;s:7:"mytitle";s:31:"Asia: Indonesia’s fresh start";s:6:"mylink";s:140:"http://www.economist.com/news/21631850-pragmatic-president-will-find-it-harder-get-things-done-nationally-he-did-locally-indonesias?fsrc=rss";s:6:"mydesc";s:1445:"UK Only Article:&amp;nbsp;\n                    standard article        \n        \n\n\n\n\n      Fly Title:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Asia        \n        \n\n\n\n      Rubric:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    The pragmatic president will find it harder to get things done nationally than he did locally        \n        \n\n\n\n      Byline:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Jon Fasman         \n        \n\n\n\n      Location:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Jakarta        \n        \n\n\n\n      Main image:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    20151101_asc001.png        \n        \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo appreciate just how unusual a figure Indonesia&rsquo;s newly elected president, Joko Widodo (known as &ldquo;Jokowi&rdquo;), cuts in his country&rsquo;s politics, compare his background with those of his four predecessors. When Suharto resigned after holding the office for 31 years, he was replaced by the vice-president, B.J. Habibie, who had spent two decades in government. Mr Habibie was followed by Abdurrahman Wahid, who under Suharto&rsquo;s rule headed Indonesia&rsquo;s biggest Muslim organisation, which his grandfather founded. Then came Megawati Sukarnoputri, daughter of the president preceding Suharto, and a former legislator and party chair; she was followed by Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, also a legislator as well as a general in ...&lt;div class="og_rss_groups"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:0:"";s:12:"itemcategory";N;s:7:"mycatid";N;s:7:"myGroup";N;s:6:"feedID";i:53171;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
