(30, 4, '2014-01-30 02:57:32', '2014-01-30 02:57:32', '<!--:en-->Land-locked Laos is one of the poorest countries in the world, but it has one thing in abundance: access to the massive Mekong River. The country’s hydropower potential has earned it the nickname “the Battery of Asia” and made it a magnet for investment from its neighbors: Thailand, southeast Asia’s second-biggest economy; Vietnam, a strategic Communist ally since the 1970s; and China, which is writing checks that put the rest to shame.<!--:-->', 'China just became the biggest investor in Laos, and Laos’s neighbors are worried', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'china-just-became-the-biggest-investor-in-laos-and-laoss-neighbors-are-worried', '', '', '2014-01-30 02:57:32', '2014-01-30 02:57:32', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=30', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(51, 4, '2014-02-13 03:40:03', '2014-02-13 03:40:03', '<!--:en-->Thailand, once the world’s biggest exporter, is short of funds to help growers under Prime Minister Yingluck Shinawatra’s 2011 program to buy the crop at above-market rates. After the government built record stockpiles big enough to meet about a third of global import demand, exports and prices have dropped, farmers aren’t being paid, and the program is the target of anti-corruption probes. Political unrest may contribute to slower growth in Southeast Asia’s second-largest economy.\n\nSelling the government inventory to pay farmers would flood the market with rice, eroding prices that in 2013 fell by the most in at least five years, and would escalate competition for shippers in Asia, including India, Vietnam and Cambodia.\n\n“The program is simply unsustainable and hurting the finances of the country,” said Concepcion Calpe, a senior economist in Rome for the United Nations’ Food &amp; Agriculture Organization. “The suspension of the rice-pledging program will exacerbate the decline in Thai market prices as farmers enrolled in the program increasingly fail to be paid.” [...]<!--:-->', 'Rice tumbling as Thailand’s unpaid farmers urge reserve sale', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'rice-tumbling-as-thailands-unpaid-farmers-urge-reserve-sale', '', '', '2014-02-13 03:40:03', '2014-02-13 03:40:03', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=51', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(160, 4, '2014-02-20 08:58:15', '2014-02-20 08:58:15', 'Efforts are being scaled up to stem a further spread of drug-resistant malaria in Southeast Asia. \n\n“The emergence of resistance… threatens worldwide malaria control and treatment since there is no alternative to this drug if its efficacy decreases further and the resistance spreads outside the region,” wrote the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria, which is providing some US$150 million for malaria prevention and elimination programmes in the Greater Mekong sub-region within the next two years. [...]\n\nIn 2008, artemisinin-resistant malaria was first discovered in Cambodia’s Pailin Province along the Thai border, which immediately alarmed health experts. [...]', 'Stepping up the fight against drug-resistant malaria in SE Asia', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'stepping-up-the-fight-against-drug-resistant-malaria-in-se-asia', '', '', '2014-02-20 08:58:15', '2014-02-20 08:58:15', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=160', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(162, 4, '2014-02-21 08:17:47', '2014-02-21 08:17:47', 'Japan''s official development assistance to the Association of Southeast Asian Nations has been an effective "investment in the future" for the 10-nation region and Japan, bolstering development and prosperity for both parties, according to a government paper released Friday.\n\nThe ODA White Paper for 2013 calls for ensuring that Japanese ODA will spur ASEAN initiatives to build infrastructure and narrow intra-regional development gaps toward the goal of boosting regional "connectivity" and achieving a more integrated economic community by the end of 2015. [...]\n\nIn 2012 [...] Vietnam was the largest recipient of Japanese ODA with $1.64 billion, followed by Afghanistan with $873 million, India with $704 million and Iraq with $360 million.\n\nAmong ASEAN countries, Cambodia ranked seventh, Myanmar 17th and Laos 18th. [...]\n\n<a href="http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/kyodo-news-international/140220/japans-oda-serves-investment-future-asean-white-paper">http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/kyodo-news-international/140220/japans-oda-serves-investment-future-asean-white-paper</a>', 'Japan''s ODA serves as "investment in future" for ASEAN: white paper', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'japans-oda-serves-as-investment-in-future-for-asean-white-paper', '', '', '2014-02-21 08:17:47', '2014-02-21 08:17:47', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=162', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(173, 4, '2014-02-24 06:20:10', '2014-02-24 06:20:10', 'Hydropower dams in parts of Southeast Asia are being canceled or suspended as governments face stronger opposition, forcing them to take greater responsibility for environmental and social impact or look to other sources of energy.\n\nThe resistance, in a region where vast hydropower potential remains untapped, occurs as energy demand is skyrocketing. With dams facing opposition over social, environmental and geopolitical factors, the days of indiscriminate building may be coming to an end, requiring countries to reconsider energy security and energy sharing in Southeast Asia.\n\nIn Vietnam, the government shelved plans for more than 420 small hydropower dams in October after a public outcry over safety. The backlash followed the deaths of dozens of people after operators felt no choice but to release water from reservoirs overwhelmed by heavy rains. Cambodia, too, is facing difficult questions about proposed new dams as alleged shoddy building resulted in dam collapses. [...]\n\nJake Maxwell Watts\n<a href="http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303448204579340180863634044?mod=googlenews_wsj">http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303448204579340180863634044?mod=googlenews_wsj</a>', 'Dam building slows in Southeast Asia', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'dam-building-slows-in-southeast-asia', '', '', '2014-02-24 06:20:10', '2014-02-24 06:20:10', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=173', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(175, 4, '2014-02-24 06:29:56', '2014-02-24 06:29:56', 'The Lower Sesan II dam project is a microcosm of the carving up of Cambodia. In one of the world’s most diverse river ecosystems, the ground burns. Whole forests are felled with scant regard for the law, while the project is backed by the country’s politically connected business elite. [...]\n\nThe 420-megawatt dam is a joint venture between Cambodian tycoon Kith Meng’s Royal Group and Hydrolancang International, a subsidiary of state-owned China Huaneng Group, which formed Hydropower Lower Sesan II Co Ltd in November 2012. [...]\n\nDaniel Pye and Phak Seangly\n<a href="http://www.phnompenhpost.com/national/waiting-deluge">http://www.phnompenhpost.com/national/waiting-deluge</a>', 'Waiting for the deluge', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'waiting-for-the-deluge-2', '', '', '2014-02-24 06:29:56', '2014-02-24 06:29:56', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=175', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(177, 4, '2014-02-24 06:34:14', '2014-02-24 06:34:14', 'Some time this year, Thai tourists may not require visas to visit Myanmar, as the exemption process has started, according to the neighbouring country''s tourism minister.\n\nHotels and Tourism Minister Htay Aung told The Nation in an exclusive interview that his ministry was currently processing the review of visa exemptions for Thai nationals.\n\nMost visitors to Myanmar are from Thailand, followed by China, Japan and South Korea. Myanmar is also popular among visitors from the United States, France, Germany and Italy.\n\nHtay Aung said the visa exemption might happen this year as Myanmar is taking the Asean chairmanship and Asean economic integration is coming at the end of 2015.\n\nMyanmar has already abolished visa requirements for nationals from Laos, Vietnam, Cambodia and the Philippines. [...]\n\nOnravee Tangmeesang \n<a href="http://www.nationmultimedia.com/business/Visa-free-travel-looms-for-Thais-heading-to-Myanma-30227522.html">http://www.nationmultimedia.com/business/Visa-free-travel-looms-for-Thais-heading-to-Myanma-30227522.html</a>', 'Visa-free travel looms for Thais heading to Myanmar', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'visa-free-travel-looms-for-thais-heading-to-myanmar', '', '', '2014-02-24 06:34:14', '2014-02-24 06:34:14', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=177', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(182, 4, '2014-02-25 06:03:57', '2014-02-25 06:03:57', 'Samart Communication Services, Loxley Wireless and Advanced Information Technology (AIT) have partnered to set up a Bt30-million joint venture, SLA Asia Co, to provide total ICT solutions in foreign markets, with the primary focus in CLMV (Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar and Vietnam).\n\nThe JV targets revenue of Bt1 billion within three years, according to Loxley executive Surakij Kiatthanakorn, who has been appointed as SLA''s chief executive officer. [...]\n\nUsanee Mongkolporn\n<a href="http://www.elevenmyanmar.com/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=5163:three-thai-ict-giants-form-jv-to-penetrate-neighbouring-markets&amp;catid=33:business&amp;Itemid=356">http://www.elevenmyanmar.com/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=5163:three-thai-ict-giants-form-jv-to-penetrate-neighbouring-markets&amp;catid=33:business&amp;Itemid=356</a>', 'Three Thai ICT giants form JV to penetrate neighbouring markets', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'three-thai-ict-giants-form-jv-to-penetrate-neighbouring-markets', '', '', '2014-02-25 06:03:57', '2014-02-25 06:03:57', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=182', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(192, 4, '2014-02-25 03:01:12', '2014-02-25 03:01:12', 'Five member states of the Association for Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), including Burma, have agreed to establish a regional Rice Federation, according to Soe Tun, joint-secretary of Myanmar Rice Federation (MRF).\n\nPlans for an ASEAN Rice Federation (ARF) began in November last year when agricultural ministers and industry leaders from Burma, Thailand, Laos, Vietnam and Cambodia convened in Bangkok. The concerned officials finalised an agreement last weekend in Rangoon. [...]\n\nAye Nai\n<a href="http://www.dvb.no/news/asean-rice-federation-in-the-works-burma-myanmar/37758">http://www.dvb.no/news/asean-rice-federation-in-the-works-burma-myanmar/37758</a>', 'ASEAN Rice Federation in the works', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'asean-rice-federation-in-the-works', '', '', '2014-02-25 03:01:12', '2014-02-25 03:01:12', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=192', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(194, 4, '2014-02-25 03:02:59', '2014-02-25 03:02:59', 'Myanmar''s top corporate leaders have called on the government to develop a roadmap to help local businesses navigate the new investment environment.\n\nCurrently, many feel the country''s investment policies are still ambiguous, and some 500 business leaders have voiced those concerns with President Thein Sein in a forum -- the first of its kind.\n\nThe business leaders hope to create awareness of the challenges local firms are facing, as the country opens its doors to foreign investments. [...]\n\nMay Wong\n<a href="http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/business/international/roadmap-urged-to-help/1011734.html">http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/business/international/roadmap-urged-to-help/1011734.html</a>', 'Roadmap urged to help Myanmar firms navigate investment environment', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'roadmap-urged-to-help-myanmar-firms-navigate-investment-environment', '', '', '2014-02-25 03:02:59', '2014-02-25 03:02:59', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=194', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(274, 4, '2014-02-28 02:04:31', '2014-02-28 02:04:31', 'More Japanese companies are choosing the Asean region over China as an investment destination as rising costs and concerns about the environment make Asia’s biggest economy less attractive, according to the Japan External Trade Organization. [...]\n\n<a href="http://www.bangkokpost.com/breakingnews/397532/asean-winning-japan-investments">http://www.bangkokpost.com/breakingnews/397532/asean-winning-japan-investments</a>', 'Asean winning Japan investments', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'asean-winning-japan-investments', '', '', '2014-02-28 02:04:31', '2014-02-28 02:04:31', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=274', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(276, 4, '2014-03-03 02:09:17', '2014-03-03 02:09:17', 'The property market in the largest northern province has flourished in recent years, spurred by a tourism boom, the entry of giant retailers and the effects of massive flooding elsewhere in 2011. \n\nIts prospects remain good alongside an expansion of Chiang Mai airport, upcoming Asean economic integration and planned investment in transport networks. \n\nThe property boom began in late 2011 when Thailand suffered heavy flooding, particularly in Bangkok. Residential demand turned to provinces, particularly major ones where facilities are good and developments are planned. [...]\n\nThe Chiang Mai-Chiang Rai motorway will link with the R3A highway, which connects southern China, Laos, Myanmar and Thailand. The province also plans to build a fourth ring road to support its growth and urban expansion. \n\n<a href="http://www.bangkokpost.com/business/finance/397861/tourism-drives-chiang-mai-property-boom">http://www.bangkokpost.com/business/finance/397861/tourism-drives-chiang-mai-property-boom</a>', 'Tourism drives Chiang Mai property boom', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'tourism-drives-chiang-mai-property-boom', '', '', '2014-03-03 02:09:17', '2014-03-03 02:09:17', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=276', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(342, 4, '2014-03-03 07:15:05', '2014-03-03 07:15:05', 'Plans to build a hydroelectric dam on the Mekong River, just inside Laos and upstream from Cambodia, are raising questions about its impact on the environment.\n\nThe World Wide Fund for Nature''s report is calling the environmental impact assessment for the proposed Don Sahong dam a “recipe for disaster.”\n\nSteve Herman\nhttp://www.voanews.com/content/wildlife-group-rebuts-environmental-assessment-for-mekong-dam-project-/1863148.html', 'Wildlife group rebuts environmental assessment for Mekong dam project', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'wildlife-group-rebuts-environmental-assessment-for-mekong-dam-project', '', '', '2014-03-03 07:15:05', '2014-03-03 07:15:05', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=342', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(347, 4, '2014-03-03 07:15:18', '2014-03-03 07:15:18', '[...] The Detroit automaker has hired Tim Zimmerman from PSA Peugeot Citroen as president of GM Southeast Asia Operations. Zimmerman, 49, has worked at Peugeot since 1986 in several management positions and will oversee GM’s expanding operations in Southeast Asia. He will be based at GM Consolidated International Operations’ new headquarters in Singapore. [...]\n\nMelissa Burden\nhttp://www.detroitnews.com/article/20140303/AUTO0103/303030093/GM-names-execs-Southeast-Asia-Thailand', 'GM names execs for Southeast Asia, Thailand', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'gm-names-execs-for-southeast-asia-thailand', '', '', '2014-03-03 07:15:18', '2014-03-03 07:15:18', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=347', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(352, 4, '2014-03-03 07:18:13', '2014-03-03 07:18:13', 'The reversal of fortunes is remarkable. Week after week Thailand has been in turmoil, red shirts and yellow shirts on the streets of the capital locked in bitter dispute which no-one seemed able to defuse and few to understand. After half a century of dramatic progress, the nation suddenly finds itself dumped in a tight political cul de sac.\n\nMeanwhile, across their long shared border, Burma, so recently the region’s pariah, basks in the sort of accolades which formerly seemed Thailand’s by right. It successfully staged the South-east Asian Games last year and this year, for the first time, holds the rotating chairmanship of the Association of South-east Asian Nations (ASEAN). The international flights into Rangoon and Mandalay are crammed with foreign businessmen and tourists. [...]\n\nPeter Popham\nhttp://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/burma-aims-to-leapfrog-southeast-asian-neighbours-after-fresh-beginning-9166686.html', 'Burma aims to leapfrog South-east Asian neighbours after fresh beginning', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'burma-aims-to-leapfrog-south-east-asian-neighbours-after-fresh-beginning', '', '', '2014-03-03 07:18:13', '2014-03-03 07:18:13', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=352', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(354, 4, '2014-03-04 07:34:10', '2014-03-04 07:34:10', '<!--:en-->Facebook, the world''s largest social networking site, is encouraging local small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) to raise e-commerce sales in social media, capitalising on trends in social commerce.\r\n\r\nThe move by the US firm aims to increase its online advertising revenue as it competes against search engine Google, said Arrow Guo, head of SMEs for Greater China and Southeast Asia of Facebook.\r\n\r\nHe said Asia-Pacific is a strategic region for Facebook in terms of user numbers and revenue growth, particularly India and Indonesia, which are among the world''s top five markets. [...]\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.bangkokpost.com/business/telecom/398017/facebook-targets-sme-advertising-in-thailand">http://www.bangkokpost.com/business/telecom/398017/facebook-targets-sme-advertising-in-thailand</a><!--:-->', '<!--:en-->Facebook targets SME advertising in Thailand<!--:-->', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'facebook-targets-sme-advertising-in-thailand', '', '', '2015-06-13 07:04:25', '2015-06-13 07:04:25', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&#038;p=354', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(358, 4, '2014-03-04 07:36:33', '2014-03-04 07:36:33', '<!--:en-->The Electoral Integrity Project has just released its annual report, comparing how countries around the world meet international standards.\r\n\r\nA joint project between Harvard University and the University of Sydney, the EIP report gave top marks to Norway, the Czech Republic and South Korea, while Zimbabwe, Belarus and Djibouti fared the worst. [...]\r\n\r\n[Professor Pippa Norris, director of the Electoral Integrity Project, Harvard University]: In particular, in Asia what we have is problems in a number of countries. These have been obviously in the headlines, countries such as Cambodia, such as Thailand, Bangladesh and all of these countries have had violence and street protests. So what we did was we asked a range of experts how they saw the problems in any election. We covered 73 elections in 66 countries during the last 18 months.\r\n\r\nWhat people said was a little surprising. Often when you think why does an election go wrong, people think about the election day, the polls, the votes, and people complain about things like voter fraud, all those being miscounted.\r\n\r\nIn fact, what we found however there was some other problems. For example, money in politics and the issue of political finance was a real issue in many countries, both in Asia and elsewhere. And issues of things like party broadcasts and how far people had a level playing field or how far it was stacked in favour of the government.\r\n\r\nSo there was some hidden problems which I think are really important for agencies trying to strengthen democratic elections.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/international/radio/program/asia-pacific/southeast-asias-electoral-systems-found-wanting/1274536">http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/international/radio/program/asia-pacific/southeast-asias-electoral-systems-found-wanting/1274536</a><!--:-->', '<!--:en-->Southeast Asia''s electoral systems found wanting<!--:-->', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'southeast-asias-electoral-systems-found-wanting', '', '', '2015-06-13 07:04:03', '2015-06-13 07:04:03', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&#038;p=358', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(391, 4, '2014-03-04 06:34:43', '2014-03-04 06:34:43', 'Thailand has a long-standing problem with human trafficking. Migrants from Myanmar, Cambodia and Laos are conscripted into its seafood industry. A report out today from the Environmental Justice Foundation suggests that, despite increasing international pressure and Thai government attention, it’s still happening.\n\nEJF found that industry operators are just working harder to avoid detection. One way they do that is to reshuffle and sell trafficked crew members while at sea, minimizing the risk of their escaping. This means victims of trafficking spend years at sea, virtually imprisoned by fishing boat operators. [...]\n\nGwynn Guilford\n<a href="http://qz.com/183773/in-thailand-the-cost-of-overfishing-is-trafficked-human-beings/#/h/51480,3/">http://qz.com/183773/in-thailand-the-cost-of-overfishing-is-trafficked-human-beings/#/h/51480,3/</a>', 'In Thailand the cost of overfishing is trafficked human beings', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'in-thailand-the-cost-of-overfishing-is-trafficked-human-beings', '', '', '2014-03-04 06:34:43', '2014-03-04 06:34:43', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=391', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(395, 4, '2014-03-05 06:36:50', '2014-03-05 06:36:50', '<!--:en-->International press has reported that Cambodia is preparing to “conquer” the US and South Korean markets, while Vietnam mostly targets Chinese, South East Asian and some African markets.\n\nCommenting about the news, Tran Cong Thang from the Vietnam Institute for the Policies on Agriculture and Rural Development said it is not a surprise at all. South Korea still has demand for rice imports, while Vietnam has also been exporting rice to South Korea. [...]\n\n<a href="http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/business/96628/cambodia-feared-to-be-a-threat-to-vietnam-s-rice.html">http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/business/96628/cambodia-feared-to-be-a-threat-to-vietnam-s-rice.html</a><!--:-->', 'Cambodia feared to be a threat to Vietnam’s rice', '', 'pending', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'cambodia-feared-to-be-a-threat-to-vietnams-rice', '', '', '2014-03-05 06:36:50', '2014-03-05 06:36:50', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=395', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(397, 4, '2014-03-04 06:38:23', '2014-03-04 06:38:23', 'Heng, a Cambodian development company, has made a big surprise when introducing its self-modified electric car.\n\nThe car, named Angkor EV 2014, is created by a local designer, manufactured by Heng Company which has set up a $20 million factory in Kandal province. [...]\n\nThe great achievement of Cambodia, the country with a fledgling manufacturing industry which has been relying on foreign imports, has surprised many other countries, including Vietnam. [...]\n\n<a href="http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/business/96628/cambodia-feared-to-be-a-threat-to-vietnam-s-rice.html">http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/business/96628/cambodia-feared-to-be-a-threat-to-vietnam-s-rice.html</a>', 'Cambodia-made car causes shocks to Vietnam’s auto industry', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'cambodia-made-car-causes-shocks-to-vietnams-auto-industry-2', '', '', '2014-03-04 06:38:23', '2014-03-04 06:38:23', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=397', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(400, 4, '2014-03-03 06:38:40', '2014-03-03 06:38:40', 'Last year, 1,954 Lao students studied in Vietnam, 495 in China, 164 in Thailand, 48 in Japan and 48 in Australia.\n\nThe Lao Government is focusing its efforts on human resource training and considers it key to managing its growing numbers of students overseas, especially in Vietnam, China, Thailand and Cambodia. [...]\n\n<a href="http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/education/96667/lao-students-flock-to-vietnam.html">http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/education/96667/lao-students-flock-to-vietnam.html</a>', 'Lao students flock to Vietnam', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'lao-students-flock-to-vietnam', '', '', '2014-03-03 06:38:40', '2014-03-03 06:38:40', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=400', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(484, 4, '2014-03-14 08:59:35', '2014-03-14 08:59:35', '<!--:en-->The Open Knowledge Conference in Geneva attracted delegates from 55 countries, indicating that open, public data is indeed becoming a global movement around the world.\n\nHow is Open Data adopted in Asia, the largest continent of this planet where 60 per cent of the world’s population live?\n\nAsia has some of the most advanced internet economies, as well as some of the least developed countries with hardly any access to information or information infrastructure, neither analogue nor digital. [...]<!--:-->', 'Open data developments in Asia', '', 'pending', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'open-data-developments-in-asia', '', '', '2014-03-14 08:59:35', '2014-03-14 08:59:35', '', 0, 'http://192.168.0.75/regional/?post_type=news&amp;p=484', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(38895, 3, '2014-03-25 18:24:11', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'You’re invited to the PPMM #21, which is scheduled for Tuesday, October. 29.  Please mark your calendar and extend the invite to your friends.\n\nWe have two very exciting presentations/discussions:\n\n1.  Paul, from <a href="http://arunatechnology.com/" target="_parent">Aruna Technology</a>,  is giving a presentation on remote sensing, using forest degradation monitoring as an example. We''re certain many remote sensing experts and people who’re interested in learning about forest degradation will find this presentation very informative.\n\n2.  Dana and Team, from <a href="http://www.ourcityfestival.org/2014/" target="_parent">Our City Festival</a>, will introduce you to the <a href="http://www.ourcityfestival.org/2014/" target="_parent">Open Call for the Our City Festival 2014</a>. Dana is passionate about  bringing arts to the public. As an art community organizer, and having realized that mapping is a powerful tool for visualizing stories, Dana is keen to explore the virtual space of Cambodia’s cities via mapping. Let’s bring [products of] mapping exercises to the public.\n\nIf you have just the perfect idea on how to use mapping exercises to help craft a story-worth-telling for Phnom Penh, and perhaps for Battambang and Siem Reap, please let us hear your idea. If you just want to be a part of such initiative, let’s exchange contact information and get the project rolling.\n\nWe''re looking forward to meeting you.\n\nPPMM Team\n\n---------\n\n<a href="https://www.facebook.com/groups/270719943021648/" target="_blank">PPMM Open Group on Facebook</a>\n\n<a href="http://phnompenhmapmeetup.wordpress.com/" target="_blank">PPMM Blog</a>\n\n<a href="https://twitter.com/PPMapMeetKH" target="_blank">PPMM Twitter</a>', '', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2014-03-25 18:24:11', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.opendevelopmentcambodia.net/?p=38895', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(45428, 3, '2014-03-25 18:24:11', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '<!--:en--><h2>Forest Cover Analysis</h2>\n\n\n\n\nOR\n\n\n\nCan do the same for each provinces.\n\nHowever, we cannot do one block of "Forest Cover Distribution by Percentage". We would have to do 6.\n(The current charts are quite a mess: Look at legends and y-axes labeling across charts). \nNumbers are too small and sometimes overlap each others. \n\nAny other solutions besides DataWrapper?\n\nIn the mean time, see a guide to chart choosing: \nhttp://extremepresentation.typepad.com/blog/files/choosing_a_good_chart.pdf\n\nNeed more than charts? http://www.visual-literacy.org/periodic_table/periodic_table.html<!--:-->', 'Testing DataWrapper', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2014-03-25 18:24:11', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.opendevelopmentcambodia.net/?p=45428', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(47299, 4, '2014-03-20 17:14:54', '2014-03-20 10:14:54', '<!--:en--><span style="color: #ff0000"><em>Ongoing (February 2014–)</em></span>\n\nThe Open Knowledge Foundation''s <a href="http://opendatahandbook.org/">Open Data Handbook</a> provides an introduction to the "legal, social and technical aspects of open data. It can be used by anyone but is especially designed for those seeking to open up data. It discusses the why, what and how of open data – why to go open, what open is, and the how to ‘open’ data."\n\nThe resource was first written in English. Since then it has been fully translated into eighteen other languages. However, the handbook is not yet available in the main languages of the Lower Mekong region: Burmese, Khmer, Thai, Lao, Vietnamese.\n\nThat''s where the open data community will hopefully step in. Following these instructions will enable you to create a translated version of this invaluable resource for your own community:\n<ol>\n<ol>\n	<li>Sign up for an account on <a href="https://www.transifex.com/projects/p/opendatahandbook/">Transifex.com</a>, a collaborative translation platform;</li>\n	<li>If you see a team where you think you could help out, then click on it and ask to join.</li>\n	<li>If your own language is not yet represented, then just click ''request language''.</li>\n</ol>\n</ol>\nOD Mekong partner organization <a href="http://www.opendevelopmentcambodia.net/">Open Development Cambodia</a> and the local <a href="http://kh.okfn.org/">Cambodia chapter</a> of the Open Knowledge Foundation are presently working to translate the Open Data Handbook into Khmer, but they are still seeking volunteers. Translation into Thai is also currently underway, but much more work remains to be done for versions corresponding to countries across the region. Check the <a href="https://www.transifex.com/projects/p/opendatahandbook/language/km/">Khmer</a> and <a href="https://www.transifex.com/projects/p/opendatahandbook/language/th/">Thai</a> pages to see the progress being made.<!--:-->', 'Localizing the Open Data Handbook', '', 'pending', 'open', 'open', '', 'localizing-the-open-data-handbook', '', '', '2014-03-20 17:14:54', '2014-03-20 10:14:54', '', 0, 'http://www.opendevelopmentmekong.net/?p=47299', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(47314, 8, '2014-03-21 10:23:02', '2014-03-21 03:23:02', '<!--:en--><h3>Background and prospects</h3>\n[caption id="attachment_47462" align="alignright" width="589"]<a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/50249220@N00/7266081496/"><img class=" wp-image-47462    " alt="Sihanoukville port (by Chris Lewis, 2012)" src="http://www.opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Sihanoukville-port.jpg" width="589" height="440" /></a> Sihanoukville port (by Chris Lewis, 2012)[/caption]\n\nFlows of goods and people are steadily increasing as the Mekong region becomes a major hub for logistics and transportation. The region’s airports, seaports, roads, railways are being strained by growth in commerce. To meet this rising demand, many expansion projects have been undertaken recently and efficiencies for cargo handling improved.\n\nThe opening up of economies such as Laos and Myanmar, along with their expected new airport infrastructure, will substantially affect regional air traffic. According to industry reports, international passenger numbers grew by 74 percent from 836,800 in 2008 to 1.5 million in 2011, and by 56.4 percent from 238,000 in 2008 to 683 million in 2011 for Myanmar and Laos, respectively. The potential for tourism in both nations may result in further increases. More broadly, ASEAN nations will see steep growth in international traffic because of open sky policies both within the region and beyond.\n\nA container terminal commissioned by Cambodia’s Phnom Penh Autonomous Port in January 2013 had already boosted container traffic at the port by over 20 percent just 10 months later. Vietnam has opened its deepest and biggest seaport, Cai Mep-Thi Vai, in one of its southern provinces. Such developments are making the region’s ports more competitive with the long-time leader in the sector, Singapore.\n\nCross-border road projects are also planned. These include thoroughfares from South China through Myanmar, Thailand, Laos, and Vietnam; an east/west corridor linking Myanmar, Thailand, Laos, and Vietnam; and another between Myanmar’s Dawei deep-sea port, Thailand’s Laem Chabang, and Cambodia.\n\nThe Mekong region’s position between eastern and southern Asia, as well as its ready access to trans-Pacific routes, provides great potential for economic growth if transport assets can be enhanced. This integration of the five lower Mekong nations into a common market, along with other ASEAN members, will require seamless connectivity between various modes of transport. However, difficulties remain in the lack of a regulation for these transportation developments and, as always, the possible adverse impact on local communities whose property or livelihoods are put at risk.\n\nSource: Southeast Asian Infrastructure magazine\n<h3>Initiatives</h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>Mekong River Commission <a title="http://www.mrcmekong.org/about-the-mrc/programmes/navigation-programme/" href="http://www.mrcmekong.org/about-the-mrc/programmes/navigation-programme/" target="_blank">Navigation Programme</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Data</h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>ASEAN-Japan Transportation Partnership\n<ul>\n	<li><a title="http://www.ajtpweb.org/statistics/compareasean/Water_Transport/Water_Transport_2012" href="http://www.ajtpweb.org/statistics/compareasean/Water_Transport/Water_Transport_2012" target="_blank">seaports/shipping</a></li>\n	<li><a title="http://www.ajtpweb.org/statistics/compareasean/Air_Transport/Air_Transport_2012" href="http://www.ajtpweb.org/statistics/compareasean/Air_Transport/Air_Transport_2012" target="_blank">airports/flights</a></li>\n	<li><a title="http://www.ajtpweb.org/statistics/compareasean/road_transport_2012" href="http://www.ajtpweb.org/statistics/compareasean/road_transport_2012" target="_blank">roads</a></li>\n	<li><a title="http://www.ajtpweb.org/statistics/compareasean/Rail_Transport/Rail_Transport_2012" href="http://www.ajtpweb.org/statistics/compareasean/Rail_Transport/Rail_Transport_2012" target="_blank">rail</a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>ASEAN Greater Mekong System GIS data\n<ul>\n	<li><a title="http://www.gms-eoc.org/gis-data?cat=5" href="http://www.gms-eoc.org/gis-data?cat=5" target="_blank">railways, airports, and economic corridors</a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li><a href="http://www.adb.org/sectors/transport/projects" target="_blank">ADB list of approved transportation projects</a></li>\n</ul>\n<a href="http://www.opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/ADB-transport-projects-for-Mekong.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-47506" alt="ADB transportation projects for the Mekong region" src="http://www.opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/ADB-transport-projects-for-Mekong.png" width="801" height="401" /></a>\n<h3>Laws and agreements</h3>\n<ul>\n	<li><a title="http://www.mrcmekong.org/assets/Publications/policies/agreement-waterway-trans-btw-Cam-n-VN-Eng.pdf" href="http://www.mrcmekong.org/assets/Publications/policies/agreement-waterway-trans-btw-Cam-n-VN-Eng.pdf" target="_blank">Agreement between the Government of the Socialist Republic of Viet Nam and the Royal Government of Cambodia on Waterway Transportation, 17 Dec 2009</a></li>\n	<li><a title="https://treaties.un.org/pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=TREATY&amp;mtdsg_no=XI-C-5&amp;chapter=11&amp;lang=en" href="https://treaties.un.org/pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=TREATY&amp;mtdsg_no=XI-C-5&amp;chapter=11&amp;lang=en" target="_blank">UNESCAP''s Trans-Asian Railway</a>, 12 April 2006</li>\n	<li><a title="http://www.asean.org/news/asean-secretariat-news/item/singapore-kunming-rail-link-project-to-sync-with-master-plan-on-asean-connectivity" href="http://www.asean.org/news/asean-secretariat-news/item/singapore-kunming-rail-link-project-to-sync-with-master-plan-on-asean-connectivity" target="_blank">ASEAN news article</a> (Aug 2011) about the Kunming-Singapore section</li>\n	<li><a title="https://treaties.un.org/Pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=TREATY&amp;mtdsg_no=XI-B-34&amp;chapter=11&amp;lang=en" href="https://treaties.un.org/Pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=TREATY&amp;mtdsg_no=XI-B-34&amp;chapter=11&amp;lang=en" target="_blank">UNESCAP''s Asian Highway Network</a>, 18 November 2003</li>\n	<li><a title="http://www.nationmultimedia.com/opinion/Greater-China-Thailand-connectivity-opens-up-new-o-30227552.html" href="http://www.nationmultimedia.com/opinion/Greater-China-Thailand-connectivity-opens-up-new-o-30227552.html" target="_blank">news article</a> (Feb 2014) about the Kunming-Bangkok section</li>\n	<li><a href="http://www.asean.org/images/archive/documents/111219-17th%20ATM_Agenda%20Item%208%2032nd%20STOM_Agenda%20Item%207.1.pdf" target="_blank">Protocol 6 on Railways Border and Interchange Stations</a> under the ASEAN Framework Agreement on Facilitation of Goods in Transit (AFAFGIT), December 2011</li>\n	<li><a href="http://www.asean.org/images/archive/documents/111219-17th%20ATM_Agenda%20Item%208%20ASAM%20Implementation%20Framework.pdf" target="_blank">The Implementation Framework of the ASEAN Single Aviation Market (ASAM)</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Documents</h3>\n[dg]<a href="http://www.opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/ADB-Mekong-transportation-assessment-2009.pdf">\n</a>\n\n<a title="http://www.mrcmekong.org/assets/Publications/basin-reports/NAP-Risk-Analysis-Vol-I-Full-report.pdf" href="http://www.mrcmekong.org/assets/Publications/basin-reports/NAP-Risk-Analysis-Vol-I-Full-report.pdf" target="_blank">Carriage, handling and storage of dangerous goods along the Mekong River, Volume I: Risk Analysis</a>, Mekong River Commission\n\n<a title="http://www.mrcmekong.org/assets/Publications/basin-reports/NAP-Recommendations-Vol-II.pdf" href="http://www.mrcmekong.org/assets/Publications/basin-reports/NAP-Recommendations-Vol-II.pdf" target="_blank">Carriage, handling and storage of dangerous goods along the Mekong River, Volume II: Recommendations</a>, Mekong River Commission<!--:-->', 'Transportation', '', 'pending', 'open', 'closed', '', 'transportation', '', '', '2014-03-21 10:23:02', '2014-03-21 03:23:02', '', 0, 'http://www.opendevelopmentmekong.net/?page_id=47314', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(47317, 8, '2014-03-21 10:24:52', '2014-03-21 03:24:52', '<!--:en-->NOTE: JavaScript is required to view interactive timelines on this page. Please ensure you have installed and enabled the latest version of JavaScript for optimal viewing. This <span style="color: #ff0000">DRAFT</span> page outlines of the status of legislation and discussion surrounding freedom of information in each of the countries of the Mekong region (Laos and Myanmar forthcoming).\n<h2>Regional overview and prospects</h2>\n[caption id="attachment_47383" align="alignright" width="552"]<a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/sara_y_tzunki/559999249/"><img class=" wp-image-47383   " alt="Bangkok internet cafe (by Sara y Tzunki, 2007)" src="http://www.opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Bangkok-internet.jpg" width="552" height="369" /></a> Bangkok internet cafe (by Sara y Tzunki, 2007)[/caption]\n\nFreedom of information (FOI) in the Mekong region has a varied history due to the uneven stances that Southeast Asian nations have taken toward accessibility and transparency in their media and technologies. The ASEAN Charter refers to freedom of expression, but not to freedom of information, an extension of that right. ASEAN’s Intergovernmental Commission on Human Rights is responsible for protecting both of these rights or promoting them where they do not exist, but FOI has not been included as a component of fulfilling the commission''s core mandate, according to the Southeast Asian Press Alliance. However, the promotion of the flow of information is now in ASEAN’s political and security pillar.\n\nAmong Southeast Asian nations, only Thailand (and Indonesia, beyond the Mekong) has a domestic law regarding FOI. While the national press laws of Cambodia and Laos have provisions for freedom of information, direct legislation is necessary to ensure that information in the public interest can be freely accessed, according to UNESCO. Although there has been some drafting of FOI laws in Vietnam, the overall state of this right is relatively low throughout the Mekong region. Even in cases of a law ostensibly in effect, implementation and practical matters continue to be challenges. Continued censorship and surveillance of online communications are especially concerning. UNESCO asserts that inadequate funding, an undeveloped culture of information sharing among public administrators, and low awareness of and demand for information have all hindered FOI.\n\nAs political unrest, especially concerning national elections in 2013 and 2014, has been a continuing theme, the need for citizens to find reasonably accurate and complete information will only increase.  Indeed, the forces of globalization and rapid socioeconomic development in the region have upset mechanisms of political control, sparking reform and progress toward more democratic and open societies.\n\nSources: Southeast Asian Press Alliance; UNESCO\n<h2>Country overviews</h2>\n<h3>Cambodia</h3>\n\n<h4>Key local institutions</h4>\n<ul>\n	<li><a title="http://www.apiinstitute.org/" href="http://www.apiinstitute.org/">Advocacy and Policy Institute</a></li>\n	<li><a title="http://www.ccimcambodia.org/" href="http://www.ccimcambodia.org/">Cambodian Center for Independent Media</a></li>\n	<li><a href="http://opendevelopmentcambodia.net">Open Development Cambodia</a></li>\n	<li><a href="http://www.open.org.kh/en">Open Institute</a></li>\n	<li><a href="http://kh.okfn.org/">Open Knowledge Foundation Cambodia</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Further resources and reading</h4>\n<ul>\n	<li><a title="http://www.ccimcambodia.org/report/FOI_survey_(30_April_2012).pdf" href="http://www.ccimcambodia.org/report/FOI_survey_(30_April_2012).pdf">Freedom of Information: Advancing Research and Actions</a>, April 2012, Cambodian Center for Independent Media</li>\n	<li><a title="http://www.article19.org/data/files/medialibrary/2739/11-09-20-Cambodia.pdf" href="http://www.article19.org/data/files/medialibrary/2739/11-09-20-Cambodia.pdf">Cambodia: Draft Law on Access to Information: Legal Analysis</a>, September 2011, Article 19</li>\n	<li><a title="http://www.cchrcambodia.org/admin/media/report/report/english/2009-01-08-%20Access%20to%20Information%20in%20Southeast%20Asia%20and%20Cambodia-%20EN.pdf" href="http://www.cchrcambodia.org/admin/media/report/report/english/2009-01-08-%20Access%20to%20Information%20in%20Southeast%20Asia%20and%20Cambodia-%20EN.pdf">Access to Information in Southeast Asia and Cambodia</a>, 2009, Raymond Leos</li>\n	<li><a href="http://www.freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-net/2013/cambodia">Freedom on the Net</a> and <a href="http://www.freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-press/2013/cambodia">Freedom of the Press</a> report cards for Cambodia, 2013, Freedom House</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Thailand</h3>\n\n<h4>Key local institutions</h4>\n<ul>\n	<li><a href="https://thainetizen.org/">Thai Netizen</a></li>\n	<li><a href="http://www.oic.go.th/content_eng/default_eng.asp">Thailand Office of the Official Information Commission</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Further resources and reading</h4>\n<ul>\n	<li><a href="http://www.ucl.ac.uk/constitution-unit/research/foi/countries/thailand">Brief on FOI in Thailand</a>, University College London Constitution Unit</li>\n	<li><a title="https://www.pcpd.org.hk/english/infocentre/files/thailand.doc" href="https://www.pcpd.org.hk/english/infocentre/files/thailand.doc">Information Access and Privacy Protection in Thailand</a>, Commissioner of Thailand''s Official Information Commission</li>\n	<li><a href="http://www.article19.org/data/files/pdfs/submissions/thailand-upr-submission.pdf">Submission to the UN Universal Periodic Review of the Kingdom of Thailand</a>, 2011, Article 19</li>\n	<li><a href="http://www.freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-net/2013/thailand">Freedom on the Net</a> and <a href="http://www.freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-press/2013/thailand">Freedom of the Press</a> report cards for Thailand, 2013, Freedom House</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Vietnam</h3>\n\n<h4>Key local institutions</h4>\n<ul>\n	<li>(forthcoming)</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Further resources and reading</h4>\n<ul>\n	<li><a href="http://www.article19.org/resources.php/resource/37111/en/vietnam:-article-19''s-submission-to-the-un-universal-periodic-review">Submission to the UN Universal Periodic Review</a>, 2013, Article 19</li>\n	<li><a href="http://www.freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-net/2013/vietnam">Freedom on the Net</a> and <a href="http://www.freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-press/2013/vietnam">Freedom of the Press</a> report cards for Thailand, 2013, Freedom House</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Laos</h3>\n(forthcoming)\n<h3>Myanmar</h3>\n(forthcoming)<!--:-->', 'Freedom of Information', '', 'pending', 'open', 'open', '', 'freedom-of-information', '', '', '2014-03-21 10:24:52', '2014-03-21 03:24:52', '', 0, 'http://www.opendevelopmentmekong.net/?page_id=47317', 0, 'page', '', 0);
