(53082, 2, '2015-01-30 06:53:55', '2015-01-30 06:53:55', '<!--:en--><blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/Aid-Development-CC-Flickr.png"><img class="wp-image-160957 size-large" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/Aid-Development-CC-Flickr-1024x588.png" alt="Aid and Development" width="100%" /></a> Photo credit: World Bank (cropped). Image published under Creative Commons 2.0 SA licence.</blockquote>\nAll countries in the Lower Mekong Basin receive official development assistance (ODA), with Thailand also contributing ODA as a donor. The LMB accounts for approximately 1 percent of the world’s total ODA received, a surprisingly low figure, given the conflicts that the region has faced in the last five decades and the resulting developmental and humanitarian challenges.\n\nThe region is experiencing three main transitions that impact development assistance:\n<ol>\n	<li>a rapidly growing urban population and an accelerating rate of urban development,</li>\n	<li>a shift from a centralized economy to more market-based economic systems that emphasize industrialization and diversification, and</li>\n	<li>the realization and importance of regional and global connectivity.</li>\n</ol>\nDonors and development assistance agencies such as the Asian Development Bank (ADB), have prioritized infrastructure projects to meet the demands brought by these transitions, including hydropower generation, road infrastructure programs, and communications technologies.<a href="#_edn1" name="_ednref1"><sup>1</sup></a> The ADB alone has funded infrastructure projects worth about US$11 billion since 1992. Large projects such as these have far-reaching (and sometimes unintended) effects across all categories of development assistance, which is driving it to become more dynamic, and increasing its importance to government agencies, private interests, and local communities. These major projects can enmesh donors in tense, inter-connected issues surrounding the projects’ environmental and social impacts.\n\nThe major donors to the five LMB countries, ranked according to monetary contribution, are:<sup><a href="#_edn2" name="_ednref2">2</a></sup>\n<ol>\n	<li>Japan</li>\n	<li>World Bank</li>\n	<li>Asian Development Bank</li>\n	<li>China<a href="#_edn3" name="_ednref3"><sup>3</sup></a></li>\n	<li>Australia</li>\n	<li>France</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n\n\n<div class="tableauPlaceholder" style="width: 100%;height: 476px"><a href=''#''><img alt=''Top 15 donors to the Lower Mekong Basin'' src=''https:&#047;&#047;publicrevizit.tableausoftware.com&#047;static&#047;images&#047;To&#047;Top15DonorstotheMekongRegion&#047;Dashboard1&#047;1_rss.png'' style=''border: none'' /></a></div>\nODA is sourced two ways: from bilateral and multilateral donors.\n\n<strong>Bilateral</strong> assistance flows directly from a donor government to a recipient government. Some key examples of bilateral donors include Japan (JICA), China, Australia, France (AFD), Switzerland (SDC), and the United States (USAID), among many others.\n\n<strong>Multilateral</strong> donors are organizations that draw from more than one government’s assistance to provide support to a country. Examples of multilateral donor organizations include the World Bank, the European Union, the Asian Development Bank, and various United Nations organizations.\n\nODA contributes to the gross national income (GNI) of nations in the LMB. World Bank data shows that in 2012, ODA comprised 6.16% of <strong>Cambodia’s </strong>GNI, placing it in the “medium aid dependency” category.<a href="#_edn4" name="_ednref4"><sup>4</sup></a> <strong>Laos</strong> received 4.87% of its GNI from ODA, while <strong>Vietnam</strong> received 2.98%. In the same year, <strong>Thailand</strong> was repaying more of its ODA than it was receiving.<a href="#_edn5" name="_ednref5"><sup>5</sup></a> For comparison, the average percentage of ODA in Africa was 2.4% of GNI in 2010.<a href="#_edn6" name="_ednref6"><sup>6</sup></a>\n\nData from the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) reveals a change within the region during 2013. The total amount of ODA received increased over the ten years to 2013 for all countries in the Mekong region with the exception of Thailand, whose ODA has had a downward trend since 2000 when the Thai government began to repay its outstanding development loans. Up until 2012, Vietnam received by far the highest annual amount of ODA of Mekong countries at US$4.1 billion, which is more than five times the amount received by the second highest recipient, Cambodia.<a href="#_edn7" name="_ednref7"><sup>7</sup></a> However, in 2013, the amount of ODA Myanmar received increased almost seven times to US$3.9 billion.<a href="#_edn8" name="_ednref8"><sup>8</sup></a>\n\nMyanmar’s increase came as it continued to remove barriers to trade and restrictions on foreign entities operating within its borders. Western donors, such as USAID, had committed only limited humanitarian aid in Myanmar following the 1962 military coup and subsequent political instability, but began expanding assistance and re-establishing local offices following moves towards greater transparency and democracy.<a href="#_edn9" name="_ednref9"><sup>9</sup></a>\n<div class="tableauPlaceholder" style="width: 100%;height: 458px"><a href=''#''><img alt=''Dashboard 1 '' src=''https:&#047;&#047;publicrevizit.tableausoftware.com&#047;static&#047;images&#047;To&#047;TotalODAOverTime1990-2012&#047;Dashboard1&#047;1_rss.png'' style=''border: none'' /></a></div>\n&nbsp;\n\nAlthough Vietnam received the highest level of ODA in 2013, Laos and Myanmar both received the highest rate of ODA per capita at US$63, followed by Cambodia (US$55), Vietnam (US$46) and Thailand (-US$0.4).<a href="#_edn10" name="_ednref10"><sup>10</sup></a> The average for the LMB was US$45, compared to the world average of US$19.<a href="#_edn11" name="_ednref11"><sup>11</sup></a>\n\n[wp-feature-box id="177458"]\n\n&nbsp;\n<h4>References</h4>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana"><a href="#_ednref1" name="_edn1">1.</a> JICA funded the Can Tho Bridge in Vietnam, for example. JICA and Mekong Delta: Inclusive and Dynamic Development. JICA (December 2010). <a href="http://www.jica.go.jp/vietnam/english/office/others/c8h0vm000001siky-att/brochure_05_en.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.jica.go.jp/vietnam/english/office/others/c8h0vm000001siky-att/brochure_05_en.pdf</a></p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana"><a href="#_ednref2" name="_edn2">2.</a> Aid Statistics. OECD. <a href="http://www.oecd.org/dac/stats/aid-at-a-glance.htm">http://www.oecd.org/dac/stats/aid-at-a-glance.htm</a></p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana"><a href="#_ednref3" name="_edn3">3.</a> This is an estimate based on various sources. China released a White Paper in 2014 that stated it gave $14.1 billion US dollars in foreign assistance (grants, interest-free loans, and concessional loans) from 2010-2012, for an average of $4.7 billion US dollars annually. Additionally, 30.5% of this assistance went to Asian countries – approximately $1433.5 million US dollars, which would likely place China below the World Bank and above Australia. Although China does not classify its assistance according to ODA standards set forth by the Development Assistance Committee (DAC), estimates are based on “ODA-like” flows. “White Paper: China’s Foreign Aid.” Information Office of the State Council, The People’s Republic of China. Beijing, China. 2014. <a href="http://www.scio.gov.cn/zxbd/wz/Document/1374915/1374915.htm">http://www.scio.gov.cn/zxbd/wz/Document/1374915/1374915.htm</a>; N. Kitano and Y. Harada. “Estimating China’s Foreign Aid 2001-2013.” JICA Research Institute. June 2014. No. 78.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana"><a href="#_ednref4" name="_edn4">4.</a> OECD defines “low aid dependency” as an ODA/GNI ratio below 3% and “high aid dependency” as greater than 9%. DAC Guidelines and Reference Series: Harmonising Donor Practices for Effective Aid Delivery. OECD Publishing. 14 April 2003. Page 111; “Net official development assistance and official aid received.” World Development Indicators, World Bank. <a href="http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/DT.ODA.ALLD.CD">http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/DT.ODA.ALLD.CD</a>; “GNI, Atlas Method.” World Development Indicators, World Bank. http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GNP.ATLS.CD.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana"><a href="#_ednref5" name="_edn5">5.</a> “Net official development assistance and official aid received.” <em>World Development Indicators,</em> World Bank. <a href="http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/DT.ODA.ALLD.CD" target="_blank">http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/DT.ODA.ALLD.CD</a></p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana"><a href="#_ednref6" name="_edn6">6.</a> “2011 OECD report on aid predictability: survey on donors’ forward spending plans 2011-2013.” OECD. <a href="http://www.oecd.org/dac/aid-architecture/49565196.pdf">http://www.oecd.org/dac/aid-architecture/49565196.pdf</a>.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana"><a href="#_ednref7" name="_edn7">7.</a> “Net official development assistance and official aid received.” <em>World Development Indicators,</em> World Bank. <a href="http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/DT.ODA.ALLD.CD" target="_blank">http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/DT.ODA.ALLD.CD</a></p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana"><a href="#_ednref8" name="_edn8">8.</a> OECD. Query Wizards for International Development Statistics. <a href="http://stats.oecd.org/qwids/#?x=2&amp;y=6&amp;f=3:51,4:1,1:1,5:3,7:1&amp;q=3:51+4:1+1:1+5:3+7:1+2:1,29,93,120,170,188+6:2004,2005,2006,2007,2008,2009,2010,2011,2012,2013" target="_blank">http://stats.oecd.org/qwids/#?x=2&amp;y=6&amp;f=3:51,4:1,1:1,5:3,7:1&amp;q=3:51+4:1+1:1+5:3+7:1+2:1,29,93,120,170,188+6:2004,2005,2006,2007,2008,2009,2010,2011,2012,2013</a></p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana"><a href="#_ednref9" name="_edn9">9.</a> “Burma: History.” U.S. Agency for International Development. <a href="http://www.usaid.gov/burma/history" target="_blank">http://www.usaid.gov/burma/history</a>.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana"><a href="#_ednref10" name="_edn10">10.</a> “Net ODA received per capita.” <em>World Development Indicators,</em> World Bank. <a href="http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/DT.ODA.ODAT.PC.ZS" target="_blank">http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/DT.ODA.ODAT.PC.ZS</a></p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana"><a href="#_ednref11" name="_edn11">11.</a> Figures based on 2013 ODA levels reported by OECD, and 2013 population figures provided by the Asian Development Bank.</p><!--:-->', 'Aid and development', '<!--:en-->Official Development Aid into the five countries of the Lower Mekong Basin accounts for just 1% of the world’s total. While Thailand began paying back its ODA debt in 2000, the amount of ODA to the four other countries increased between 2004 and 2013. <!--:-->', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'aid-and-development-assistance', '', '', '2015-01-30 06:53:55', '2015-01-30 06:53:55', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=53082', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
