(85432, 6, '2015-03-03 10:46:34', '2015-03-03 10:46:34', '<!--:en--><blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Samutprakarn_Khlong_Lat_Pho_3.jpg"><img src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Samutprakarn_Khlong_Lat_Pho_3.jpg" alt="Bhumibol Bridge, in Bangkok. Photograph by Sivakrit Saravit. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 4.0 International, 2015." width="100%" /></a> Bhumibol Bridge, in Bangkok. Photograph by Sivakrit Saravit. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 4.0 International, 2015.</blockquote>\nInfrastructure is the constructed part of the landscape that facilitates transportation, business, and communication. Roads, <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/energy/">energy</a>, water, marketplaces, and information and tele-communications hardware are all examples of infrastructure.\n\nA lack of sufficient infrastructure can prevent access to various services and can limit the growth of a developing country’s <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/economy-and-commerce/">economy</a>. However, the relationship between infrastructure investment and economic growth is not as simple as a direct correlation. Some analysts believe that the results of such investment must be measured by the extent that they create a sustainable, valuable flow of services.<sup><a href="#_edn1" name="_ednref1">1</a></sup>\n<h4>Investment</h4>\nAs something benefiting both the public and private sectors, <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/aid-and-development-assistance/">infrastructure development</a> can be undertaken by either state, multilateral, or commercial entities. In the Mekong region, much transportation infrastructure has been built with <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/aid-and-development-assistance/">aid from other nations</a>, particularly China, Japan, and Australia.\n\nThese nations may view the financial assistance they provide as an investment, not only in the development of Southeast Asia’s capacity, but also in their own interests in the region.\n\nThe Asian Development Bank (ADB), which is led by Japan, estimates its annual lending for infrastructure is less than 2 percent of the US$750 billion per year that it projects will be needed in Asia between 2010 and 2020.<sup><a href="#_edn2" name="_ednref2">2</a></sup> The Japanese International Cooperation Agency has also provided hundreds of millions of dollars in funding for several major infrastructure projects throughout the Mekong region over the past several decades.\n\nGreater urbanization and industrialization are driving the increased demand, which Mekong nations are experiencing at relatively high rates, along with rapid population growth. The United Nations estimated that there was a 50 percent increase in urban <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/population-and-census/">populations in the Mekong region</a> within the past ten years.<sup><a href="#_edn3" name="_ednref3">3</a></sup>\n\nThe ADB’s Greater Mekong Subregion program aims to reduce poverty through growth from infrastructure development, but projects in the program have also had adverse effects on some communities, according to Oxfam Australia.<sup><a href="#_edn4" name="_ednref4">4</a></sup> Data from ADB shows that a majority of its transportation funding has been spent on roads, especially in Vietnam, while relatively little has been delegated for rail, air, or other forms of transport infrastructure. Similarly, a significant proportion of the World Bank''s funding has also gone towards roads and highways in the region. The OPEC Fund for International Development had committed a total of $300 million across Cambodia, Vietnam, Thailand, Myanmar and Laos for development of transport, energy, and water supply and sanitation as of December 2014.\n\n\n<div class="tableauPlaceholder" style="width: 100%;height: 719px">&amp;lt;a href=''http:&amp;amp;#47;&amp;amp;#47;opendevelopmentmekong.net&amp;amp;#47;briefings&amp;amp;#47;infrastructure&amp;amp;#47;''&amp;gt;&amp;lt;img alt=''WB Infrastructure LMB '' src=''https:&amp;amp;#47;&amp;amp;#47;public.tableau.com&amp;amp;#47;static&amp;amp;#47;images&amp;amp;#47;Wo&amp;amp;#47;WorldBankinfrastructureprojectsintheMekongregion_1&amp;amp;#47;WBInfrastructureLMB&amp;amp;#47;1_rss.png'' style=''border: none'' /&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt;</div>\n&nbsp;\n\nThere are two more recent developments in this sector. One is the Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank, created by China in October 2014 with the support of 21 nations in the region. The new bank is expected to help address the financing gap as it announced a US$40 billion infrastructure fund, while also giving China greater influence in relevant decision-making. The other is the US-backed Smart Infrastructure for the Mekong<sup><a href="#_edn5" name="_ednref5">5</a></sup>, a program announced in 2013, offering scientific and technical assistance to facilitate environmentally and socially conscious infrastructure development in the five lower Mekong countries.\n\nHowever, both these initiatives remain in the early stages and have yet to sponsor any projects, leaving ADB and the World Bank as the major sources of infrastructure funding, along with national governments. Contributions to such development from privately-owned corporations is difficult to determine, since it is decentralized and often poorly documented. Analysts assert that government funds and bank credit will continue to be the predominant sources of infrastructure financing, with Vietnam and Myanmar two of the top recipients, among other Southeast Asian nations.\n<h4>Telecommunications</h4>\nFor telecommunications, trends in the Mekong region reflect those worldwide: a growing number of citizens in the region are becoming connected through mobile devices with Internet access. This is reflected in ADB statistics for the region in 2013, showing an average of 2.7 internet subscribers per 100 population, compared with 96.4 mobile phone subscribers per 100 population. There is also a marked difference between rural and urban environments in the levels of telecom distribution and use. The number of fixed line telephone subscribers for the LMB ranges from just 1 per 100 in Myanmar to 10.1 per 100 in Vietnam. The average across the five countries in the region is just 6.6 per 100 population.\n\nRegulation of the telecommunications and media sector is in flux in Mekong nations, with governments struggling to keep up with technological progress and the political implications. Competition between service providers has also characterized the sector, except in Myanmar, where telecom was entirely operated by the government until reforms for more openness in 2012. Satellite and submarine cable networks are the next generation of infrastructure that will further increase the region’s connection to the rest of the world.<sup><a href="#_edn6" name="_ednref6">6</a></sup>\n<h4>Water and power</h4>\nPopulation growth and urbanization are placing strain on the region’s water and <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/energy/">power</a> infrastructure, such as plumbing systems and electrical grids. The construction of <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/hydropower/">hydroelectric dams</a> has been particularly contentious due to the environmental, land use and political implications for those downstream.\n\nReporting on Millennium Development Goals (MDG), ADB statistics for 2012 show an average of 84 percent of people with access to improved drinking water sources, and 69.4 percent of people with access to improved sanitation facilities across the LMB.\n\nAccording to a publication by Global Infrastructure Monitor, much of Southeast Asia is turning from natural gas to coal to generate electricity, since natural gas supplies are falling and exports rising.<sup><a href="#_edn7" name="_ednref7">7</a></sup> In 2015, Thailand and Myanmar are set to offer new concessions for oil and gas blocks, driven by increasing gas demand and oil prices. The five LMB countries have also been under consideration for involvement in the ASEAN Power Grid<sup><a href="#_edn8" name="_ednref8">8</a></sup>, which would connect neighboring countries to better balance electrical loads.\n\nAs with other ASEAN campaigns, it remains to be seen how well the LMB countries will fare alongside larger, more advanced economies in terms of infrastructure development in all its forms.\n<h4>Transportation</h4>\nTransport by land, air, and sea is vital for the movement of people and goods from place to place. Infrastructure in these categories includes highways, railways, airports, and sea/river shipping ports, all of which are found in the Mekong region. Land routes are the most commonly used form of transport for domestic and intra-regional travel, given the availability of bus services between major cities and across national borders. Common trips over land include Bangkok to or from Phnom Penh and Phnom Penh to or from Ho Chi Minh, as well as Phnom Penh to or from Vientiane.\n\nThailand leads the region in number of registered motor vehicles, while Vietnam has the greatest length of paved roads, according to a 2013 publication of the ASEAN-Japan Transport Partnership. However, Myanmar''s growth rate of vehicle ownership is the highest, while Cambodia''s growth rate of road-length-per-1000-square-kilometers was highest. From the same publication, Thailand and Vietnam also had the greatest railway lengths and largest amounts of international sea cargo throughput. Thailand far outpaced the other Mekong countries in international air cargo loaded and international air passenger traffic. However, ADB data shows that most of its transportation funding since 1998 has been spent in Vietnam, on road projects.\n\n&nbsp;\n<blockquote>Some other notable infrastructure developments affecting the Mekong region include the following:\n\n1. The Trans-Asian Railway and the Asian Highway, projects of the United Nations Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific\n2. The Greater Mekong Subregion Information Superhighway and the Backbone Telecommunications Network, projects of the Asian Development Bank\n3. The Cambodian-Vietnamese Super Highway Telecoms Network, a joint project of Telecom Cambodia and Vietnam Telecom International</blockquote>\n&nbsp;\n\n[wp-feature-box id="177088"]\n\n&nbsp;\n<h4>References</h4>\n<span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ednref1" name="_edn1">1</a>. World Bank. The contributions of infrastructure to economic development (1993). <a href="http://elibrary.worldbank.org/doi/pdf/10.1596/0-8213-2628-7" target="_blank">http://elibrary.worldbank.org/doi/pdf/10.1596/0-8213-2628-7</a>. Accessed 22 January 2015.</span>\n\n<span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ednref2" name="_edn2">2</a>. S.R. The Economist. ''Why China is creating a new "World Bank" for Asia'', 11 November 2014. <a href="http://www.economist.com/blogs/economist-explains/2014/11/economist-explains-6">http://www.economist.com/blogs/economist-explains/2014/11/economist-explains-6</a>. Accessed 22 January 2015.</span>\n\n<span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ednref3" name="_edn3">3</a>. UN Habitat. Challenges facing the Mekong region. <a href="http://mirror.unhabitat.org/content.asp?typeid=19&amp;catid=465&amp;cid=2375">http://mirror.unhabitat.org/content.asp?typeid=19&amp;catid=465&amp;cid=2375</a>. Accessed 22 January 2015.</span>\n\n<span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ednref4" name="_edn4">4</a>. Oxfam Australia. Those behind infrastructure development. <a href="https://www.oxfam.org.au/explore/infrastructure-people-and-environment/those-behind-infrastructure-development/">https://www.oxfam.org.au/explore/infrastructure-people-and-environment/those-behind-infrastructure-development/</a>. Accessed 22 January 2015.</span>\n\n<span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ednref5" name="_edn5">5</a>. Lower Mekong Initiative. Smart infrastructure for the Mekong factsheet (2013). <a href="http://lowermekong.org/news/smart-infrastructure-mekong-factsheet">http://lowermekong.org/news/smart-infrastructure-mekong-factsheet</a>. Accessed 22 January 2015.</span>\n\n<span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ednref6" name="_edn6">6</a>. Evans, Peter. Paul Budde Communication, ''Asia - Fixed Telecommunications Infrastructure'' (2014). <a href="http://www.budde.com.au/Research/Asia-Fixed-Telecommunications-Infrastructure.html">http://www.budde.com.au/Research/Asia-Fixed-Telecommunications-Infrastructure.html</a>. Accessed 22 January 2015.</span>\n\n<span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ednref7" name="_edn7">7</a>. Southeast Asia Infrastructure. Towards energy security. <a href="http://southeastasiainfra.com/towards-energy-security/">http://southeastasiainfra.com/towards-energy-security/</a>. Accessed 22 January 2015.</span>\n\n<span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ednref8" name="_edn8">8</a>. ASEAN. Memorandum of understanding on the ASEAN power grid. <a href="http://www.asean.org/communities/asean-economic-community/item/memorandum-of-understanding-on-the-asean-power-grid">http://www.asean.org/communities/asean-economic-community/item/memorandum-of-understanding-on-the-asean-power-grid</a>. Accessed 22 January 2015.</span>\n\n<span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size: 10pt"> </span><!--:-->', 'Infrastructure', '<!--:en-->In the Mekong region, much transportation infrastructure has been built with aid from other nations, particularly China, Japan, and Australia. Greater urbanization and industrialization are driving the increased demand, which Mekong nations are experiencing at relatively high rates, along with rapid population growth. Two recent developments in this sector are the Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank created by China in October 2014, and  the US-backed Smart Infrastructure for the Mekong program announced in 2013.<!--:-->', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'infrastructure', '', '', '2015-03-03 10:46:34', '2015-03-03 10:46:34', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=85432', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
