(177266, 8, '2015-04-09 11:07:36', '2015-04-09 11:07:36', '<!--:en--><em><strong>This page is under development, with additions and updates forthcoming.</strong></em>\n<blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Scarabeo9_Thailand.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-177268" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Scarabeo9_Thailand-1024x768.jpg" alt="Scarabeo9_Thailand" width="760" height="570" /></a>\nAn oil drilling platform near Phuket, Thailand. Photograph: Vidar Lokken, 2011, Wikimiedia Commons. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0.</blockquote>\n&nbsp;\n\nActivities related to mining, oil and natural gas have been controversial throughout the Mekong, often bringing powerful corporate interests into conflict with the livelihoods of average citizens. There is a close relationship between these extractive industries and a nation’s energy needs and economic output.\n\nData from 2012 collected by the US Geological Survey<sup><a href="#_edn1">1</a></sup> stated that cement, sand, clay, stone and gemstones were mined in all five countries of the lower Mekong, while iron, gold, copper, lead, zinc, tin, silver, gypsum and coal were mined in all countries except Cambodia.\n\nCambodia’s extractive industries remain in a relatively early stage of development, having begun only in the past 10 to 15 years. In comparison, Myanmar’s oil and natural gas industries are more mature, with several major onshore and offshore projects that started decades ago, according to Extractive Industries Watch,<sup><a href="#_edn2">2</a></sup> an online portal that is aiming to improve governance of the sector. The same source has reported that Vietnam has minor reserves of oil, coal and minerals, while there are two large coal fields and potentially lucrative gas reserves in the country. Laos is considered to be relatively low in mineral resources.\n\n\n<div class="tableauPlaceholder" style="width: 654px;height: 519px"><a href=''http:&#047;&#047;opendevelopmentmekong.net&#047;topics&#047;extractive-industries&#047;''><img alt=''Dashboard 1 '' src=''https:&#047;&#047;public.tableau.com&#047;static&#047;images&#047;Ex&#047;ExtractiveExports&#047;Dashboard1&#047;1_rss.png'' style=''border: none'' /></a></div>\nAlthough Thailand produces oil and natural gas, it also imports both to meet increasing domestic demand. The country’s oil supply is limited, but it holds large reserves of natural gas, according to analysis<sup><a href="#_edn3">3</a></sup> undertaken by the US Department of Energy in 2014.\n\nRegulation of extractive industries in the region is difficult to characterize due to the range of individual cases, but campaigns such as the Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative<sup><a href="#_edn4">4</a></sup> have made some progress. Myanmar is under consideration for EITI membership, which would affirm its commitment to disclosure of relevant information.\n<h4><span style="font-family: ''andale mono'', times">References</span></h4>\n<a href="#_ednref1">1.</a> <a href="http://minerals.usgs.gov/minerals/pubs/country/asia.html">http://minerals.usgs.gov/minerals/pubs/country/asia.html</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref2">2.</a> <a href="http://www.eiwatch.org/">http://www.eiwatch.org/</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref3">3.</a> <a href="http://www.eia.gov/countries/country-data.cfm?fips=th">http://www.eia.gov/countries/country-data.cfm?fips=th</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref4">4.</a> <a href="https://eiti.org/">https://eiti.org/</a><!--:-->', 'Extractive industries', '<!--:en-->Activities related to mining, oil and natural gas have been controversial throughout the Mekong, often bringing powerful corporate interests into conflict with the livelihoods of average citizens. USGS data from 2012 stated that cement, sand, clay, stone and gemstones were produced in all five countries of the Lower Mekong Basin. Regulation of extractive industries in the region is difficult to characterize due to the range of individual cases, but campaigns such as the Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative have made some progress.<!--:-->', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'extractive-industries', '', '', '2015-04-09 11:07:36', '2015-04-09 11:07:36', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=177266', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
