(177464, 8, '2015-04-09 12:07:58', '2015-04-09 12:07:58', '<!--:en--><em><strong>This page is under development, with additions and updates forthcoming.</strong></em>\n<blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/13335253903_4e16dbfe53_k.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-177465" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/13335253903_4e16dbfe53_k-1024x499.jpg" alt="13335253903_4e16dbfe53_k" width="760" height="370" /></a>\nThe Golden Triangle, at the borders of Myanmar, Thailand and Laos. Photograph: Marcus Molina, Flickr, 2013. Licensend under Creative Commons Attribution Share-Alike 2.0.</blockquote>\n&nbsp;\n\nThe ownership and control of land is of critical importance in understanding the Mekong region and its development. Because a majority of the population is primarily engaged in agriculture, land is the basis of both residence and livelihood. The five nations encompass a total land area of 1.9 million square kilometers; in geographic size, Myanmar is the largest and Cambodia the smallest.\n\nAccording to USAID,<sup><a href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1">1</a></sup> there are varying land policies in the region. Thailand’s land administration is deemed to be relatively transparent and efficient, having issued title deeds to many of its population. In contrast, there is wide disparity in Cambodia’s landholdings, and enforcement is problematic. Reclamation of land by the state has caused disputes with residents, similar to cases of conflict between Cambodian community members and corporations that have been granted concessions for commercial development.\n\nIn Vietnam, Laos, and Myanmar, land belongs to the population as a whole, with the government administering it on behalf of the people—there is no private ownership. Individuals and organizations rely on land-use rights.\n<h4>References</h4>\n<a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1">1</a> <a href="http://usaidlandtenure.net/">http://usaidlandtenure.net/</a>\n\n&nbsp;<!--:-->', 'Land', '<!--:en-->The ownership and control of land is of critical importance to understanding the Mekong region and its development. A majority of the population is primarily engaged in agriculture, so land is the basis of both residence and livelihood. The five nations encompass a total land area of 1.9 million square kilometers; in geographic size, Myanmar is the largest and Cambodia the smallest.\n[This page is under development, with additions and updates forthcoming.]<!--:-->', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'land', '', '', '2015-04-09 12:07:58', '2015-04-09 12:07:58', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=177464', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
(177470, 10, '2015-04-09 13:15:11', '2015-04-09 13:15:11', '<!--:en--><em><strong>This page is under development, with additions and updates forthcoming.</strong></em>\n<blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/6279842281_2004f6d027_b.jpg"><img class="wp-image-177471 size-large" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/6279842281_2004f6d027_b-1024x685.jpg" alt="An SH-60F Sea Hawk helicopter surveys the flooded Bangkok area, 2011. Photo by Navy Visual News Service. Licensed underAttribution 2.0 Generic. " width="100%" height="100%" /></a> An SH-60F Sea Hawk helicopter surveys a flooded area in Bangkok, 2011. Photo by Jennifer Villalovos. Licensed under Attribution 2.0 Generic.</blockquote>\n&nbsp;\n\nThe Mekong region faces its share of natural disasters, especially flooding from the monsoonal rains typical of its climate. Climate change is expected to exacerbate these problems and also bring rising sea levels. According to a 2014 report<sup><a href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1">1</a></sup> by the United Nations, those living in coastal regions of Asia will be the most affected by such changes, making emergency response and long-term planning even more critical in mitigating the effects. Vietnam is especially vulnerable to seasonal Pacific typhoons due to its long coastline and the towns and cities situated along it.\n\nLarge-scale accidents and man-made disasters also threaten the environment and public safety. For example, an oil spill occurred off the coast of Thailand’s Rayong province in 2013, with varying estimates of the amount and the damage caused. The aftermath showed the difficulty of reacting in a coordinated way, as with natural disasters. While both Thailand and Vietnam have considered the development of nuclear power, which would introduce new risks to the region, to date no Mekong nation has moved forward with this.\n\nThe Red Cross, an international humanitarian aid organization, is active throughout the Mekong when the need arises, as are other local and international aid organisations. Each of the five lower Mekong nations is a member of the Asian Disaster Reduction Center<sup><a href="#_ftn2" name="_ftnref2">2</a></sup>, which works to enhance disaster resilience through gathering and dissemination of relevant information as well as a satellite detection program.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h4>References</h4>\n<span style="font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1">[1]</a> <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/mar/22/global-warming-hit-asia-hardest">http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/mar/22/global-warming-hit-asia-hardest</a></span>\n\n<span style="font-size: 10pt"> </span><span style="font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ftnref2" name="_ftn2">[2]</a> <a href="http://www.adrc.asia/">http://www.adrc.asia/</a></span>\n\n&nbsp;<!--:-->', 'Disasters and emergency response', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'disasters-and-emergency-response', '', '', '2015-04-09 13:15:11', '2015-04-09 13:15:11', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=177470', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
(179089, 10, '2015-04-10 04:20:07', '2015-04-10 04:20:07', '<!--:en--><em><strong>This page is under development, with additions and updates forthcoming.</strong></em>\n\n&nbsp;\n<blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/7999065754_912c809ac1_k.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-179090" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/7999065754_912c809ac1_k-1024x768.jpg" alt="A Vietnamese factory worker. Photo by the International Labor Organization, 2008. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivs 2.0 Generic" width="100%" height="100%" /></a> A Vietnamese factory worker. Photo by the International Labor Organization, 2008. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivs 2.0 Generic</blockquote>\n&nbsp;\n\nWithin ASEAN, the Mekong region is seen as holding a vital part of Southeast Asia’s industrial potential. Thailand, as the second-largest economy after Indonesia, is a manufacturing hub. As defined by Open Development Mekong, the industry category includes not only manufacturing but also construction and tourism, which are important sources of employment and income in the region.\n\nKey sectors for the Mekong country economies include:\n\n<strong>Thailand</strong> – tourism, garments and textiles, agricultural processing\n\n<strong>Vietnam</strong> – food processing, garments\n\n<strong>Laos</strong> – mining, timber and agricultural processing\n\n<strong>Myanmar</strong> – minerals, agricultural and forest products\n\n<strong>Cambodia</strong> – garments, tourism, agricultural products.\n\nAccording to IHS Global Insight<sup><a href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1">1</a></sup>, manufacturing in the Mekong region could be stimulated by the forthcoming implementation of ASEAN’s Economic Community integration plan as well as further development of infrastructure and production from multinational corporations. Wage increases in China may also create an opportunity for more manufacturing to move to the Mekong.\n\nConstruction is dependent on the development of infrastructure, residential and commercial spaces, and facilities for other sectoral activities (hydropower dam construction is considered separately). As the economies of the region continue to grow, rising costs for labor and materials could slow construction. Investment from China, Japan, and Korea funds a significant portion of building projects throughout the Mekong.\n\nIn a 2011 ADB report<sup><a href="#_ftn2" name="_ftnref2">3</a></sup>, Cambodia had the highest cumulative annual growth rate in tourism from 2000 to 2009, at 17.85%, followed by Laos at 11.78%. In 2010, tourism accounted for 18.3% of Cambodia’s gross domestic product, a higher amount than any other nation in the region, although a 3% decline by 2020 is forecast. The same report stated that Cambodia’s and Lao’s tourism from international sources is strongly influenced by casino-gaming development. There are at least 32 casinos in the border areas of Cambodia and Laos, which suggests strong demand from Thailand and the China, where casino gambling is illegal.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h4> References</h4>\n<span style="font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1">[1] </a>Chandaran, Nyshka "Is This Asia''s New Manufacturing Hub?" CNBC, published December 29, 2014 <a href="http://www.cnbc.com/id/102295748">http://www.cnbc.com/id/102295748</a></span>\n\n<span style="font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ftnref2" name="_ftn2">[2] </a>Asian Development Bank, "Greater Mekong Subregion: Tourism Sector Assessment, Strategy and Roadmap," September, 2011. Accessed February, 2015.<a href="http://www.adb.org/sites/default/files/institutional-document/33310/files/gms-tourism-assessment.pdf">  http://www.adb.org/sites/default/files/institutional-document/33310/files/gms-tourism-assessment.pdf</a></span><!--:-->', 'Industry', '<!--:en-->The Mekong region holds a vital part of Southeast Asia’s industrial potential. As defined by Open Development Mekong, the industry category includes not only manufacturing, but also construction and tourism, which are important sources of employment and income in the region.\n[This page is under development, with additions and updates forthcoming.]<!--:-->', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'industry', '', '', '2015-04-10 04:20:07', '2015-04-10 04:20:07', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=179089', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
(179098, 10, '2015-04-10 04:49:12', '2015-04-10 04:49:12', '<!--:en--><em><strong>This page is under development, with additions and updates forthcoming.</strong></em>\n<blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/14578286573_74f45b093f_k.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-179104" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/14578286573_74f45b093f_k-1024x768.jpg" alt="Traffic police in Phnom Penh, photo by Iwan Gabovitch, 2014. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution 2.0 Generic" width="760" height="570" /></a>Traffic police in Phnom Penh, photo by Iwan Gabovitch, 2014. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution 2.0 Generic</blockquote>\n&nbsp;\n\nThe percentage of the total population living in urban areas ranges from 20% in Cambodia to 31% in Vietnam, 32% in Myanmar and 34% in Laos and Thailand. The annual rate of change ranges from 1.6% in Thailand to 4.4% in Laos<sup>1</sup>.\n\nThis demographic shift from the countryside to metropolitan areas will not only concentrate populations but create even greater reliance on water, food, and energy distribution systems often beyond the control of city administrations, as noted in a 2013 publication by the Institute for Social and Environmental Transition. This raises serious questions for urban planners and administrators about how to cope with the ever-increasing needs of residents.\n\nAccording to the same publication<sup>2</sup>, much of the urbanization occurring in the Mekong is found along water bodies; most urban inhabitants in the Mekong region work as day laborers or small-scale salespeople, making their incomes relatively low and unreliable. Although official rates of urban poverty are lower than rural ones, income inequality is high in many cities, where multiple levels of society are juxtaposed. The Institute also stated that despite decentralization of public administration in Mekong nations and increased decision-making at sub-national levels, current urban governance and planning is weak across the region, with limited technical capacity within local government agencies.\n\nThe constantly-changing urban landscape means that some neighborhoods are experiencing gentrification, as wealthier residents and businesses catering to them seek new areas to settle, often out-pricing and displacing long-time inhabitants. While this trend is not unique to the Mekong, it has been remarkably sped-up due to the pace of economic growth.\n\nBangkok (with 8.5 million people in the city and 14 million in the wider metropolitan area) and Ho Chi Minh City (with 9 million in the metropolitan area) are the largest population centers in the Mekong. Although the capital cities of Mekong nations are also usually their most populated and economically active, Vietnam (where Hanoi is the capital) and Myanmar (where Naypyidaw is the capital but Yangon is the largest city) are exceptions.\n<h4><span style="font-size: 12pt"> Reference</span></h4>\n[1] "<span style="font-size: 10pt">CIA World Factbook Country Profiles" accessed on April 5, 2015</span> <a href="https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/" target="_blank">https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/</a>\n<h4><span style="font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1">[2]</a> Friend, R., &amp; MacClune, K. (2013). <em>Regional integration in the Mekong: Challenges of urbanization and climate change</em>. Boulder, CO: Institute for Social and Environmental Transition-International. <a href="http://i-s-e-t.org/resources/working-papers/mekong-integration.html">http://i-s-e-t.org/resources/working-papers/mekong-integration.html</a></span></h4>\n&nbsp;<!--:-->', 'Urban administration', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'urban-administration', '', '', '2015-04-10 04:49:12', '2015-04-10 04:49:12', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=179098', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
(179277, 10, '2015-04-10 06:00:41', '2015-04-10 06:00:41', '<!--:en--><em><strong>This page is under development, with additions and updates forthcoming.</strong></em>\n<blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/7635995124_526f381d96_k.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-179280" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/7635995124_526f381d96_k-1024x768.jpg" alt="The Supreme Court in Phnom Penh, photo by Barry Price, 2012. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivs 2.0 Generic" width="100%" height="100%" /></a> The Supreme Court in Phnom Penh, photo by Barry Price, 2012. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivs 2.0 Generic</blockquote>\nThe legal framework, legal/court systems, and law enforcement are all included in this category. As a cornerstone of common structures of government, along with executive and legislative branches, the judiciary is of great significance in contributing to the context in which environmental and socioeconomic development occurs.\n\nThe basis of law in these countries is as follows:\n\n<strong>Cambodia</strong>: legislation by parliament, as well as the Constitution\n\n<strong>Laos</strong>: law-making single party\n\n<strong>Myanmar</strong>: law-making single party until contested elections in 2010\n\n<strong>Thailand</strong>: legislation by parliament; civil law but with influence from common law\n\n<strong>Vietnam</strong>: law-making single party using communist legal theory and French civil law\n\nAccording to a 2010 book<sup><a href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1">1</a></sup> by experts in this area, although governments of the Mekong nations acknowledge in theory the rule of law in maintaining political legitimacy and social order, in practice the judicial system is often susceptible to influence by powerful individuals. In all Mekong nations, ruling elites do not always accept limits imposed by the judiciary, and interference in proceedings is common in both judicial and civil cases. Thus, courts and other legal institutions in the Mekong region are often unable act with integrity.\n\nLaw enforcement is also problematic in this region, because officials serve in agencies that are non-transparent and open to corruption. Based on connections and wealth, infractions of varying severity can be dismissed or the normal penalties waived. Although some enforcement agents take their jobs seriously, they struggle against endemic apathy and “business as usual.” Tourists are commonly warned by their home governments that local police in the Mekong are unreliable, and even residents do not fare much better in their dealings, in many cases. Transparency International ranked each of the Mekong nations in the bottom third of its 2014 index of corruption perceptions<sup><a href="#_ftn2" name="_ftnref2">2</a></sup>.\n\nASEAN agreements that the nations of the Mekong region have signed onto also shape the legal context in various sectors. Examples include the 2002 ASEAN Agreement<sup><a href="#_ftn3" name="_ftnref3">3</a></sup> on Transboundary Haze Pollution and the 1992 ASEAN Free Trade Area<sup><a href="#_ftn4" name="_ftnref4">4</a></sup>. Additionally, the Mekong Regional Law Center<sup><a href="#_ftn5" name="_ftnref5">5</a></sup> is an organization representing the legal communities of Cambodia, Laos, Thailand, and Vietnam that has been established to promote the rule of law and facilitate legal development within member nations. The center operates programs to enhance legal capacity and encourage complementarity of legal systems.\n<h4>Reference</h4>\n<span style="font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1">[1] </a>Stuart-Fox, M. "Historical and Cultural Constraints on Development in the Mekong," in <em>Globalization and Development in the Mekong Economies</em>, Monograph Books, Ch. 11, p224, July 30, 2010 <a href="http://www.elgaronline.com/view/9781848444829.00022.xml">http://www.elgaronline.com/view/9781848444829.00022.xml</a></span>\n\n<span style="font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ftnref2" name="_ftn2">[2] </a>"Corruption Perceptions Index 2014 : Results," Transparency International, 2014, <a href="https://www.transparency.org/cpi2014/results">https://www.transparency.org/cpi2014/results</a></span>\n\n<span style="font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ftnref3" name="_ftn3">[3]</a> "ASEAN Agreement on Transbounday Haze and Pollution," 2002, <a href="http://haze.asean.org/?wpfb_dl=32">http://haze.asean.org/?wpfb_dl=32</a></span>\n\n<span style="font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ftnref4" name="_ftn4">[4]</a> "ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA Council)" accessed April 8, 2015 <a href="http://www.asean.org/communities/asean-economic-community/category/asean-free-trade-area-afta-council">http://www.asean.org/communities/asean-economic-community/category/asean-free-trade-area-afta-council</a></span>\n\n<span style="font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ftnref5" name="_ftn5">[5]</a> "Mekong River Law Center," published December 12, 2001, accessed April 8, 2015 <a href="http://www.mekonglawcenter.org/index.asp">http://www.mekonglawcenter.org/index.asp</a></span>\n\n<span style="font-size: 10pt"> </span><!--:-->', 'Law and judiciary', '<!--:en-->As a cornerstone of common structures of government, along with executive and legislative branches, the judiciary is of great significance in contributing to the context in which environmental and socioeconomic development occurs.\n[This page is under development, with additions and updates forthcoming.]<!--:-->', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'law-and-judiciary', '', '', '2015-04-10 06:00:41', '2015-04-10 06:00:41', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=179277', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
