(287073, 1, '2015-06-09 21:51:29', '2015-06-09 21:51:29', '<!--:en-->&nbsp;\n<blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/MekongFishing_ChristineAndrada3.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-68982" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/MekongFishing_ChristineAndrada3-1024x576.jpg" alt="Mekong River fishing. Photograph by Christine Andrada. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Non Commercial 2.0." width="100%" /></a> Mekong River fishing. Photograph by Christine Andrada. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Non Commercial 2.0.</blockquote>\nThe Lower Mekong Basin (LMB) is moving from largely agrarian fishing and farming countries, to agro-industrial sectors where people farm cash crops rather than those that directly supply their families'' needs. While there are many crops and food products across the LMB, rice and fish still contribute the most to both their <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/economy-and-commerce/">economies</a> and sustaining their <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/population-and-census/">populations</a>.\n\nThe main crops grown in the LMB include rice, corn (maize), sugar, soy beans, cassava, coffee and rubber. Rubber exports alone accounted for US$19.7 billion in 2011 for the region.<a href="#_edn1" name="_ednref1"><sup>1</sup></a>. Following a decline in Brazilian coffee exports, Vietnam was the number one producer of commodity coffee globally in 2014.\n\n<strong>Commodity exports in 2011 (FAO)</strong>\n<h6 class="tableauPlaceholder" style="width: 100%; height: 717px;"><a href="#"><img style="border: none;" src="https://public.tableau.com/static/images/LM/LMBExports2011/LMBExports2011/1_rss.png" alt="LMB Exports 2011 " /></a></h6>\nThe region has seen a trend towards value-added processing for agricultural and fish products, rather than selling raw materials. Thailand and Vietnam have been doing this for many years with fermented and dried fish for use in the manufacture of products such as sauces and pastes.\n\nThe LMB produced more than 100 million tons of paddy rice in 2014, almost 15 percent of the world total.<a href="#_edn2" name="_ednref2"><sup>2</sup></a> While a large percentage of this rice goes to local trade and within the countries, the region is also a significant exporter of rice to the world. In fact, Laos is the only country of the LMB not to rank in the top ten countries in the world for rice exports. <a href="#_edn3" name="_ednref3"><sup>3</sup></a> This is why the Mekong Basin has been called the “rice bowl of Asia”.\n\n<a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/mekong-river-basin/">The Mekong River system</a> supports the world’s largest inland fishery. Its annual harvest of 2.2 million tonnes of fish has an estimated retail market value between US$4.3 and US$7.8 billion<sup><a href="#_edn4" name="_ednref4">4</a></sup>.\n\nThe River is second only to the Amazon River in the <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/environment-and-natural-resources/">biodiversity</a> it supports. The people who live along its banks and within reach of its rich fisheries depend on it as a food source, as it is estimated to supply 75% of people’s protein in some areas<sup><a href="#_edn5" name="_ednref5">5</a></sup>.\n<div class="tableauPlaceholder" style="width: 100%; height: 619px;"><a href="#"><img style="border: none;" src="https://public.tableau.com/static/images/LM/LMBfishproduction1950-2010/LMBFishProduction1950-2010/1_rss.png" alt="LMB Fish Production 1950-2010 " /></a></div>\nThe region also has access to significant ocean fisheries in the Andaman Sea, Gulf of Thailand, and South China Sea. Thailand and Vietnam were the number three and four top global exporters of fish and fishery products respectively in 2012, based on value<a href="#_edn6" name="_ednref6"><sup>6</sup></a>.\n\nThe effects of increased use of chemicals, pesticides and fertilizers in intensive farming of crops and aquaculture have not been significantly measured in the region. With the exception of Myanmar, all LMB countries have approved the Rotterdam Convention on the trade and use of pesticides internationally<a href="#_edn7" name="_ednref7"><sup>7</sup></a>, and have government representation for reporting and information sharing. It is unclear, however, what level of pesticide or chemical governance is carried out within those four countries.\n\nAt the 2014 FAO Regional Conference for Asia and the Pacific, representatives from the region committed to achieving the Millennium Development Goal of halving extreme hunger by strengthening policy and reporting around food security. Agricultural reporting from countries across Asia has decreased in quality and quantity over the last decade, and this is seen as a first step towards better food security measures.<sup><a href="#_edn8" name="_ednref8">8</a></sup>\n\n[wp-feature-box id="177279"]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>References</h4>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana; font-size: small;"><a href="#_ednref1" name="_edn1">1</a>. Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (2015). Retrieved from <a href="http://faostat3.fao.org/download/T/TP/E" target="_blank">http://faostat3.fao.org/download/T/TP/E</a>. Search terms: Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar, Thailand, Vietnam, 2011, Rubber, natural dry. Accessed 6 February 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana; font-size: small;"><a href="#_ednref2" name="_edn2">2</a>. Total 2014 paddy rice production of LMB countries: 104,641,000t; Total global 2014 paddy rice production: 707,480,000 t. World Rice Statistics. <a href="http://ricestat.irri.org:8080/wrs">http://ricestat.irri.org:8080/wrs</a>. Accessed 6 February 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana; font-size: small;"><a href="#_ednref3" name="_edn3">3</a>. US Department of Agriculture; Economic Research Service (2014). Principle rice exporting countries worldwide in 2013 (in 1,000 metric tons of milled equivalent) In <em>USDA - Agricultural Statistics 2013, page I-20</em>. <a href="http://www.statista.com/statistics/255947/top-rice-exporting-countries-worldwide-2011/" target="_blank">http://www.statista.com/statistics/255947/top-rice-exporting-countries-worldwide-2011/</a>. Accessed 6 February 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana; font-size: small;"><a href="#_ednref4" name="_edn4">4</a>. Hortle, K.G. (2009) Fisheries of the Mekong river basin. In Campbell, I.C., editor. <em>The Mekong. Biophysical environment of a transboundary river</em>. Elsevier.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana; font-size: small;"><a href="#_ednref5" name="_edn5">5</a>. Hortle, K.G. (2007) Consumption and the yield of fish and other aquatic animals from the Lower Mekong Basin. <em>MRC Technical Paper No. 16</em>, Mekong River Commission, Vientiane. 87 pp.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana; font-size: small;"><a href="#_ednref6" name="_edn6">6</a>.Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (2014). <em>The state of world fisheries and aquaculture: Opportunities and challenges</em>. <a href="http://www.fao.org/3/a-i3720e.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.fao.org/3/a-i3720e.pdf</a>. Accessed 9 February 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana; font-size: small;"><a href="#_ednref7" name="_edn7">7</a>. United Nations. Rotterdam Convention. <a href="http://www.pic.int/Countries/Statusofratifications/tabid/1072/language/en-US/Default.aspx%23a-note-1">http://www.pic.int/Countries/Statusofratifications/tabid/1072/language/en-US/Default.aspx#a-note-1</a>. Accessed 8 April 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana; font-size: small;"><a href="#_ednref8" name="_edn8">8</a>. Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations. FAO Regional Office for Asia and the Pacific: Strengthening food and nutritional security. <a href="http://www.fao.org/asiapacific/perspectives/food-security/en/" target="_blank">http://www.fao.org/asiapacific/perspectives/food-security/en/</a>. Accessed 9 April 2015.</p><!--:-->', 'Agriculture and fishing', '<!--:en-->The Lower Mekong Basin is moving from largely agrarian fishing and farming countries, to agro-industrial sectors where people farm cash crops rather than those that directly supply their families’ needs. While there are many crops and food products across the LMB, rice and fish still contribute the most to both their economies and to sustaining their populations.<!--:-->', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '61872-autosave-v1', '', '', '2015-06-09 21:51:29', '2015-06-09 21:51:29', '', 61872, 'http://odm.dev/2015/06/09/61872-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
